    morphology: 'Extremely thin (0.1 x 10-20 µm) spirals with characteristic hooked ends (resembling a question mark).',
    hostRange: 'Virtually all mammals. Rodents are the universal maintenance hosts.',
    reservoir: 'Maintenance hosts (rats, mice, dogs, pigs, cattle) carry specific serovars (e.g., Rats -> Icterohaemorrhagiae, Dogs -> Canicola, Cattle -> Hardjo).',
    vectors: 'None.',
    carrierState: 'Maintenance hosts harbor leptospires in the proximal renal tubules for life, shedding billions in urine asymptomatically.',
    envSurvival: 'Survives for months in warm, stagnant, neutral-to-alkaline freshwater and moist soil.',
    transmission: 'Direct: Contact with infected urine. Indirect: Contact with urine-contaminated water/soil (swimming, floods, rice farming). Penetrates intact mucous membranes or abraded skin.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Skin abrasions or mucous membranes.',
      spread: 'Rapid hematogenous spread (viremia/bacteremia phase), causing endothelial damage, followed by localization in the kidneys, liver, and reproductive tract.',
      organs: [ 'Kidneys', 'Liver', 'Placenta', 'Eye' ],
      lesions: 'Acute interstitial nephritis, centrilobular hepatic necrosis, widespread petechiae.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Humoral immunity clears the spirochetes from the blood, but they hide in immunologically privileged sites (renal tubules, anterior chamber of the eye).',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: "Dogs: Acute renal failure, jaundice, fever, vomiting. Calves: Fever, hemolytic anemia, 'red water' (hemoglobinuria).",
        chronic: "Cattle/Pigs: Late-term abortion, stillbirths, agalactia ('flabby bag' syndrome in dairy cows), equine recurrent uveitis (moon blindness).",
        subclinical: 'Maintenance hosts (e.g., rats) are asymptomatic.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: "Biphasic: 1) Septicemic phase (fever, severe myalgia, conjunctival suffusion). 2) Immune phase (Weil's disease: severe jaundice, acute kidney injury, pulmonary hemorrhage).",
        chronic: 'Fatigue, uveitis.',
        subclinical: 'Common in endemic areas.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Icterus (jaundice), generalized petechial hemorrhages, pale swollen kidneys.',
    histopathology: 'Tubulointerstitial nephritis. Spirochetes visible in tubules using silver stains (Warthin-Starry).',
    sampleCollection: 'Blood (acute phase), Urine (after week 1), Serum (paired acute/convalescent).',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'Microscopic Agglutination Test (MAT) is the gold standard serological test.',
    rapidTests: 'Point-of-care IgMs available (e.g., SNAP Lepto).',
    serology: 'MAT requires live cultures of numerous serovars (specialized labs only).',
    pcr: 'Real-time PCR on blood or urine is replacing MAT for rapid diagnosis.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Dogs: Ehrlichiosis, Babesiosis, Infectious Canine Hepatitis. Humans: Dengue, Malaria, Viral Hepatitis, Hantavirus.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Animals/Humans: Penicillin G (acute phase) to save lives; Doxycycline to clear the renal carrier state.',
    drugResistance: 'None significant.',
    vaccination: 'Inactivated multivalent bacterins (protect against clinical disease but do not reliably prevent renal shedding).',
    biosecurity: 'Rodent control. Avoid stagnant water.',
    control: 'Vaccination of pets and livestock. Draining wetlands on farms.',
    prevention: 'Wearing protective clothing/boots for agricultural workers and sewer workers.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'The most widespread zoonosis globally. Major outbreaks occur following flooding and monsoons in tropical regions.',
    onehealth: 'Requires urban rodent control, pet vaccination, and occupational safety measures for farmers and sanitation workers.',
    economicImportance: 'Significant losses in dairy/swine industries due to abortion and reduced milk yield.',
    indianContext: 'Highly endemic, especially during the monsoon season (e.g., Mumbai floods, Kerala). Often misdiagnosed as Dengue.',
    globalContext: 'Worldwide, but heavily concentrated in the tropics.',
    recentAdvances: 'Recombinant vaccines (e.g., targeting LigA/LigB proteins) are in development to prevent renal colonization.',
    keyTakeHome: "Spirochete shed in urine. Rats are reservoirs. Causes Weil's disease (jaundice/renal failure) in humans, abortion in livestock. Associated with floods.",
    quickRevision: "Spirochete, rat urine, hooked ends, Weil's disease, interstitial nephritis, MAT, Warthin-Starry, Doxycycline.",
    references: [ 'WHO Leptospirosis', 'OIE Terrestrial Manual' ]
  },
  tuberculosis: {
    definition: 'Bovine Tuberculosis (bTB) is a chronic, progressive, granulomatous infectious disease primarily caused by Mycobacterium bovis, affecting cattle and causing zoonotic TB in humans.',
    historicalBackground: 'Koch discovered M. tuberculosis in 1882. Theobald Smith differentiated human and bovine bacilli in 1898. Pasteurization was introduced partly to combat milk-borne TB.',
    etiology: 'Mycobacterium bovis. Member of the Mycobacterium tuberculosis complex (MTBC). Acid-fast, aerobic, non-motile bacillus.',
    taxonomy: 'Phylum Actinomycetota, Class Actinomycetes, Order Mycobacteriales, Family Mycobacteriaceae.',
    morphology: 'Slender rods. Cell wall rich in mycolic acids (lipid), making it Gram-stain resistant but Acid-Fast positive.',
    hostRange: 'Cattle, Buffalo, Deer, Badgers, Possums. Humans.',
    reservoir: 'Infected cattle herds. Wildlife reservoirs complicate eradication (e.g., Badgers in UK, Possums in NZ, White-tailed deer in USA).',
    vectors: 'None.',
    carrierState: 'Latent infection can persist for years before reactivation.',
    envSurvival: 'Survives for months in feces, soil, and dark, damp environments. Extremely resistant to standard disinfectants, but killed by sunlight and pasteurization.',
    transmission: 'Animals: Aerosol (close contact in housing) or ingestion (calves drinking infected milk). Humans: Ingestion of unpasteurized milk (causing cervical/intestinal TB) or aerosol (slaughterhouse workers).',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Inhalation into alveoli or ingestion.',
      spread: 'Phagocytosed by alveolar macrophages, prevents phagolysosome fusion. Multiplies intracellularly, spreading to regional lymph nodes. Hematogenous spread to other organs.',
      organs: [
        'Lungs',
        'Lymph nodes (Retropharyngeal, Bronchial, Mediastinal)',
        'Pleura',
        'Udder'
      ],
      lesions: 'Classic tubercle (granuloma): central caseous necrosis (cheese-like), surrounded by epithelioid macrophages, Langhans giant cells, and a fibrous capsule. Often calcifies.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Strong Cell-Mediated Immunity (CMI) involving Th1 cells, IFN-gamma, and macrophages walls off the infection (granuloma formation). Humoral immunity is ineffective.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Rare (miliary TB).',
        chronic: 'Progressive emaciation, chronic low-grade fever, harsh dry cough (worse on exercise), enlarged superficial lymph nodes.',
        subclinical: 'Most cattle are asymptomatic until the advanced stages.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Usually latent.',
        chronic: 'Zoonotic TB: Cervical lymphadenopathy (Scrofula), intestinal TB, or pulmonary TB indistinguishable from M. tuberculosis. Fever, night sweats, weight loss.',
        subclinical: 'Latent TB infection.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: "Yellow, caseous, calcified, encapsulated nodules (tubercles) in the lungs and lymph nodes. 'Pearl disease' on the pleura.",
    histopathology: 'Caseating granulomas with acid-fast bacilli (red rods) visible via Ziehl-Neelsen staining inside Langhans giant cells.',
    sampleCollection: 'Lymph nodes (mediastinal, bronchial) at slaughter. Unpasteurized milk.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'Culture (Lowenstein-Jensen medium) takes 4-8 weeks. Post-mortem histopathology.',
    rapidTests: 'Antemortem: Single Intradermal Cervical Tuberculin Test (SICTT).',
    serology: 'Interferon-gamma release assay (IGRA / BOVIGAM) used as a supplementary test to detect cellular immunity.',
    pcr: 'Real-time PCR on tissue or milk.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Cattle: Contagious Bovine Pleuropneumonia (CBPP), Actinobacillosis, Lymphoma, Echinococcosis (lung cysts), Corynebacterium pseudotuberculosis.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Animals: Prohibited (Test and Slaughter). Humans: Prolonged (6-9 months) multi-drug therapy (Isoniazid, Rifampin, Ethambutol, Pyrazinamide - note M. bovis is naturally resistant to Pyrazinamide).',
    drugResistance: 'M. bovis is intrinsically resistant to Pyrazinamide.',
    vaccination: 'Animals: BCG vaccination is banned in many countries as it interferes with tuberculin testing (no DIVA). Humans: BCG vaccine (derived from M. bovis) used globally to prevent severe childhood TB.',
    biosecurity: 'Strict control of animal movements. Badger culling/fencing in the UK.',
    control: 'Test-and-slaughter (using SICTT). Abattoir surveillance.',
    prevention: 'Milk pasteurization entirely eliminates the public health risk from ingestion.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Historically a massive killer of children (via milk). Zoonotic TB still accounts for a significant percentage of human TB in developing nations.',
    onehealth: 'Eradication is stalled in countries (like the UK) due to intractable wildlife reservoirs, necessitating complex ecological management alongside veterinary testing.',
    economicImportance: 'Huge costs associated with testing programs, slaughter compensation, and trade restrictions.',
    indianContext: 'Highly prevalent in dairy cattle. Test-and-slaughter is not feasible due to religious bans on cattle slaughter; control relies on segregation and milk boiling.',
    globalContext: 'Eradicated from Australia. Endemic in Africa, Asia, and parts of Europe/Americas.',
    recentAdvances: 'Development of a DIVA-compatible BCG vaccine/skin test system to allow cattle vaccination without compromising surveillance.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Acid-fast bacilli causing caseating granulomas. Raw milk transmits it to humans. Test and slaughter using tuberculin skin test.',
    quickRevision: 'M. bovis, acid-fast, caseous necrosis, Langhans giant cells, raw milk, tuberculin test, Pyrazinamide resistant, badgers.',
    references: [ 'WOAH Bovine Tuberculosis', 'WHO Zoonotic TB' ]
  },
  rabies: {
    definition: 'Rabies is a rapidly progressive, invariably fatal, acute viral encephalomyelitis of all warm-blooded animals, including humans, transmitted primarily via the bite of an infected animal.',
    historicalBackground: 'Known since antiquity (c. 2000 BC). Louis Pasteur developed the first vaccine in 1885 using desiccated spinal cords of infected rabbits.',
    etiology: 'Rabies virus (RABV). Enveloped, bullet-shaped, negative-sense single-stranded RNA virus.',
    taxonomy: 'Order Mononegavirales, Family Rhabdoviridae, Genus Lyssavirus.',
    morphology: 'Bullet-shaped virion (75 x 180 nm) with glycoprotein spikes projecting from a host-derived lipid envelope.',
    hostRange: 'All mammalian species are susceptible. Reservoirs are restricted to Carnivora and Chiroptera (bats).',
    reservoir: 'Dogs (global primary reservoir for human rabies), Foxes, Raccoons, Skunks, Mongooses, and Bats.',
    vectors: 'None.',
    carrierState: 'True asymptomatic carrier state does not exist. Animals shed virus briefly before death.',
    envSurvival: 'Extremely fragile outside the host. Destroyed rapidly by sunlight, heat, desiccation, and standard disinfectants.',
    transmission: 'Saliva via bite wounds (most common). Scratches, aerosol (bat caves), or organ transplantation (rare).',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Virus introduced into muscle/subcutaneous tissue via bite.',
      spread: 'Local replication in muscle cells, binding to nicotinic acetylcholine receptors at neuromuscular junctions. Retrograde axoplasmic transport (at 1-2 cm/day) to the dorsal root ganglia and CNS. Centrifugal spread from CNS via peripheral nerves to salivary glands.',
      organs: [ 'Brain', 'Spinal cord', 'Salivary glands', 'Cornea' ],
      lesions: 'Severe viral encephalitis with minimal gross pathology.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Virus evasion via the blood-brain barrier. Death typically occurs before a robust neutralizing antibody response mounts.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: "Prodromal phase (change in behavior), followed by 'Furious' form (aggression, roaming, hypersalivation) or 'Dumb' form (paralysis, dropped jaw, choking).",
        chronic: 'Rapidly fatal (death within 3-10 days of clinical onset).',
        subclinical: 'Variable incubation period (weeks to months), but always fatal once clinical.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Fever, paresthesia at bite site. Progresses to encephalitic (furious) rabies: hydrophobia (spasms of swallowing muscles), aerophobia, hyperactivity, coma. Paralytic rabies (20% of cases) mimics Guillain-Barré.',
        chronic: 'Invariably fatal once signs appear. Very rare survivors suffer profound neurological deficits.',
        subclinical: 'Prolonged asymptomatic incubation period.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Often unremarkable. May see gastric foreign bodies (stones/wood ingested during furious phase) and congestion of the meninges.',
    histopathology: 'Non-suppurative encephalomyelitis. Negri bodies (intracytoplasmic eosinophilic inclusion bodies) pathognomonic, mostly in Purkinje cells (herbivores) or hippocampus (carnivores).',
    sampleCollection: 'Brain stem (medulla/pons), cerebellum, and hippocampus from deceased animal (cold, not frozen). Human: Nuchal skin biopsy, saliva.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'Direct Fluorescent Antibody (DFA) test on fresh brain tissue is the gold standard.',
    rapidTests: 'Lateral flow assays available but DFA remains standard due to 100% required sensitivity.',
    serology: 'RFFIT or FAVN to determine neutralizing antibody titers (for pre-exposure prophylaxis monitoring).',
    pcr: 'RT-PCR on saliva, skin biopsies, or CSF (used primarily in human antemortem diagnosis).',
    differentialDiagnosis: "Canine distemper, Aujeszky's disease (Pseudorabies), Lead poisoning, Toxoplasmosis, Traumatic brain injury.",
    treatmentPrinciples: 'No effective treatment once clinical signs appear. Milwaukee protocol (induced coma) has a negligible success rate.',
    drugResistance: 'Not applicable.',
    vaccination: 'Inactivated vaccines (tissue culture/avian embryo) highly effective for pre-exposure (PrEP) and post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP).',
    biosecurity: 'Strict handling of suspected rabid animals. Use of PPE during necropsy.',
    control: 'Mass dog vaccination (70% coverage required to break transmission cycle). Oral Rabies Vaccination (ORV) for wildlife via baits.',
    prevention: 'Prompt wound washing (soap and water for 15 mins) + human rabies immune globulin (HRIG) + vaccine series immediately after exposure.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Causes ~59,000 human deaths annually, mostly children in Asia/Africa via dog bites. 100% preventable with timely PEP.',
    onehealth: 'The quintessential One Health paradigm: human rabies elimination is impossible without mass dog vaccination and humane dog population management.',
    economicImportance: 'Massive global expenditure on human PEP, livestock losses, and dog vaccination campaigns.',
    indianContext: 'India accounts for ~36% of global human rabies deaths. Dog-mediated rabies is endemic across the country, driven by large free-roaming dog populations.',
    globalContext: 'Eliminated from domestic dogs in Western Europe and North America (where wildlife maintains the virus). Endemic in Asia and Africa.',
    recentAdvances: 'Development of novel mRNA rabies vaccines and monoclonal antibodies to replace expensive HRIG.',
    keyTakeHome: '100% fatal, 100% preventable. Centripetal nerve travel, Negri bodies, hydrophobia, managed via mass dog vaccination and immediate wound washing/PEP.',
    quickRevision: 'Rhabdovirus, bullet-shape, Negri bodies, DFA test, hydrophobia, dog bite, ascending paralysis, post-exposure prophylaxis.',
    references: [ 'WHO Rabies', 'OIE Terrestrial Manual' ]
  },
  nipah: {
    definition: 'Nipah virus (NiV) is a highly pathogenic paramyxovirus causing severe acute respiratory distress and fatal encephalitis in pigs and humans.',
    historicalBackground: 'Emerged in Malaysia in 1998, initially causing disease in pigs, which then transmitted the virus to abattoir workers and pig farmers.',
    etiology: 'Nipah virus. Enveloped, single-stranded negative-sense RNA virus.',
    taxonomy: 'Order Mononegavirales, Family Paramyxoviridae, Genus Henipavirus.',
    morphology: 'Pleomorphic, enveloped virions with surface glycoproteins (G and F).',
    hostRange: 'Pigs (amplifier host), Humans, Fruit bats (reservoir), Dogs, Cats, Horses.',
    reservoir: 'Pteropid fruit bats (flying foxes).',
    vectors: 'None.',
    carrierState: 'Bats shed virus asymptomatically in saliva, urine, and feces.',
    envSurvival: 'Survives for days in fruit juice/sap (e.g., raw date palm sap) but is susceptible to heat and standard disinfectants.',
    transmission: '1) Direct contact with infected pigs (Malaysia outbreak). 2) Consumption of date palm sap contaminated with bat urine/saliva (Bangladesh/India outbreaks). 3) Human-to-human nosocomial transmission.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Respiratory/oropharyngeal route.',
      spread: 'Infects respiratory epithelium and endothelial cells. Widespread vasculitis leads to tissue infarction, ischemia, and crossing of the blood-brain barrier.',
      organs: [ 'Lungs', 'Brain', 'Kidneys' ],
      lesions: 'Systemic necrotizing vasculitis, pulmonary edema, encephalitis.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Strong inflammatory response, cytokine storm contributes to severe acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS).',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: "Pigs ('Barking Pig Syndrome'): Severe acute febrile respiratory disease, loud harsh barking cough, neurological signs (trembling, muscle fasciculations), high morbidity, low mortality.",
        chronic: 'Usually resolves or animal is culled.',
        subclinical: 'Bats show no signs.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Fever, headache, dizziness, vomiting, rapid progression to severe atypical pneumonia, ARDS, and encephalitis (seizures, coma within 24-48h). High case fatality rate (40-75%).',
        chronic: 'Relapse of encephalitis can occur months or years after recovery.',
        subclinical: 'Rare.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Pigs: Severe pulmonary edema, congestion, consolidation. Brain: Meningeal congestion.',
    histopathology: 'Widespread fibrinoid necrosis of small blood vessels (vasculitis), syncytial (multinucleated giant) cells in respiratory epithelium and endothelium, intracytoplasmic inclusions.',
    sampleCollection: 'Throat/nasal swabs, CSF, serum, tissues (handled in BSL-4 facility).',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'RT-PCR on throat swabs or CSF. Virus isolation (BSL-4 only).',
    rapidTests: 'None widely available for point-of-care.',
    serology: 'ELISA for IgG/IgM in serum or CSF.',
    pcr: 'Real-time RT-PCR is the gold standard for rapid confirmation during outbreaks.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Pigs: Swine Influenza, PRRS, PCV2, Classical Swine Fever. Humans: Japanese Encephalitis, Rabies, Malaria, Bacterial meningitis.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Intensive supportive care. No proven specific antivirals, though Ribavirin and monoclonal antibodies are experimental.',
    drugResistance: 'Not applicable.',
    vaccination: 'None currently approved for humans or pigs. Hendra virus vaccine (Equivac HeV) provides cross-protection but is not used in pigs.',
    biosecurity: 'Extreme biosecurity. Mass culling of infected pig populations. BSL-4 required for virus isolation.',
    control: 'Banning the planting of fruit trees near pig farms. Culling infected/exposed pig herds (Malaysia eradicated it via culling over 1 million pigs).',
    prevention: 'Avoid drinking raw date palm sap. Avoid contact with sick pigs. Strict infection control (PPE) in hospitals.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'WHO Blueprint priority pathogen due to its epidemic potential, human-to-human transmission capability, and lack of countermeasures.',
    onehealth: 'Emergence driven by ecological changes (deforestation) pushing bats into agricultural interfaces (pig farms and date palm plantations).',
    economicImportance: 'Devastated the Malaysian pig industry. Causes massive public panic during human outbreaks.',
    indianContext: 'Repeated highly fatal outbreaks in Kerala (human-to-human and bat-to-human), distinct from the Malaysian pig-to-human route.',
    globalContext: 'Currently restricted to South and Southeast Asia (Malaysia, Bangladesh, India, Singapore).',
    recentAdvances: 'Development of human monoclonal antibody (m102.4) for compassionate use post-exposure.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Fruit bat reservoir. High mortality encephalitis and ARDS in humans. Transmitted via pigs (Malaysia) or raw date palm sap/human contact (India/Bangladesh).',
    quickRevision: 'Paramyxovirus, flying foxes, barking pig syndrome, date palm sap, syncytial cells, vasculitis, high mortality.',
    references: [ 'WHO Nipah', 'OIE Terrestrial Manual' ]
  },
  kyasanur: {
    definition: 'Kyasanur Forest Disease (KFD) is an acute, highly pathogenic tick-borne viral hemorrhagic fever primarily affecting monkeys and humans in Southern India.',
    historicalBackground: 'First identified in 1957 in the Kyasanur Forest of Karnataka, India, following a massive die-off of monkeys.',
    etiology: 'Kyasanur Forest Disease Virus (KFDV). Enveloped, positive-sense single-stranded RNA virus.',
    taxonomy: 'Family Flaviviridae, Genus Flavivirus. Belongs to the tick-borne encephalitis (TBE) serocomplex.',
    morphology: 'Spherical enveloped virion (40-50 nm).',
    hostRange: 'Primarily primates (black-faced langur, bonnet macaque) and humans. Small mammals (shrews, rodents) act as amplifying hosts.',
    reservoir: 'Rodents and shrews. Monkeys act as amplifying hosts but die rapidly.',
    vectors: 'Ticks, primarily Haemaphysalis spinigera.',
    carrierState: 'Small mammals can be asymptomatic carriers. Ticks transmit the virus transstadially and transovarially.',
    envSurvival: 'Maintained primarily in the tick-host life cycle.',
    transmission: 'Bite of infected Haemaphysalis ticks. Also exposure to infected monkey carcasses.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Tick bite introduces virus into the skin.',
      spread: 'Local replication in dendritic cells, systemic spread to RES, leading to severe viremia, endothelial damage, and coagulopathy.',
      organs: [ 'Liver', 'Spleen', 'Kidney', 'Brain' ],
      lesions: 'Hemorrhage due to thrombocytopenia and endothelial injury.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Inflammatory cytokine response contributes to capillary leak and hemorrhagic manifestations.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: "Monkeys (Macaques/Langurs): Sudden death ('Monkey fever').",
        chronic: 'Not applicable.',
        subclinical: 'Rodents/shrews are asymptomatic.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Sudden onset high fever, frontal headache, severe myalgia, prostration. Hemorrhagic symptoms (epistaxis, hematemesis, melena).',
        chronic: 'Biphasic illness: after 1-2 weeks of fever, a second phase with meningoencephalitis can occur.',
        subclinical: 'Rare.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Monkeys: Generalized hemorrhage, focal hepatic necrosis, splenomegaly.',
    histopathology: 'Hemorrhage, edema, and mononuclear cell infiltration in liver and kidneys. Encephalitis in the second phase.',
    sampleCollection: 'Blood/Serum during acute phase. Handled in BSL-3/4 facilities.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'RT-PCR (acute phase). MAC-ELISA for IgM.',
    rapidTests: 'None routine.',
    serology: 'IgM ELISA (positive 5 days post-onset).',
    pcr: 'Real-time RT-PCR is the gold standard for early diagnosis.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Dengue fever, Malaria, Typhoid, Leptospirosis, CCHF.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Supportive care (hydration, blood transfusions for hemorrhage). No specific antiviral.',
    drugResistance: 'Not applicable.',
    vaccination: 'Formalin-inactivated tissue culture vaccine used in endemic areas (Karnataka), though efficacy varies.',
    biosecurity: 'Tick precautions. Extreme care handling monkey carcasses.',
    control: 'Tick control (acaricides), restricting human movement into affected forests during tick season (Jan-May).',
    prevention: 'Vaccination of populations bordering forests. Wearing protective clothing and tick repellents.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Major regional public health threat causing seasonal hemorrhagic fever outbreaks with ~3-10% mortality.',
    onehealth: 'Deforestation and expansion of human settlements into forests disrupt the tick-rodent-monkey cycle, driving zoonotic spillover.',
    economicImportance: 'Impacts livelihood of forest-dwelling communities and cashew nut workers.',
    indianContext: 'Historically confined to Shimoga (Karnataka) but recently expanding to neighboring states (Kerala, Goa, Maharashtra).',
    globalContext: 'Alkhurma hemorrhagic fever virus (AHFV) in Saudi Arabia is a very closely related variant.',
    recentAdvances: 'Development of improved PCR diagnostics to rapidly differentiate KFD from Dengue in acute settings.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Tick-borne Flavivirus causing hemorrhagic fever. Epidemics heralded by sudden monkey deaths in South India.',
    quickRevision: 'Flavivirus, Haemaphysalis tick, Monkey fever, hemorrhagic, Karnataka, biphasic, rodents reservoir.',
    references: [ 'NCDC India KFD Guidelines' ]
  },
  dermatophytosis: {
    definition: 'Dermatophytosis (Ringworm) is a superficial fungal infection of keratinized tissues (hair, skin, nails) affecting various animal species and humans.',
    historicalBackground: "Recognized since antiquity. The term 'ringworm' originated from the belief that the circular lesions were caused by worms.",
    etiology: 'Fungi of the genera Microsporum (e.g., M. canis) and Trichophyton (e.g., T. verrucosum, T. mentagrophytes).',
    taxonomy: 'Kingdom Fungi, Phylum Ascomycota, Order Onygenales, Family Arthrodermataceae.',
    morphology: 'Septate branching hyphae and characteristic macroconidia (e.g., boat-shaped in Microsporum, cigar-shaped in Trichophyton) and microconidia.',
    hostRange: 'Extremely broad. Affects dogs, cats, cattle, horses, rodents, and humans.',
    reservoir: 'Cats (M. canis), cattle (T. verrucosum), rodents (T. mentagrophytes), and geophilic species in soil.',
    vectors: 'Fomites (brushes, clippers, bedding, halters) act as mechanical vectors.',
    carrierState: 'Asymptomatic carrier cats (especially long-haired breeds like Persians) are a major source of M. canis.',
    envSurvival: 'Spores (arthroconidia) can survive in the environment, on shed hairs, and on fomites for up to 18-24 months.',
    transmission: 'Direct contact with infected animals, or indirect contact with contaminated fomites or soil.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Arthroconidia adhere to corneocytes on abraded skin.',
      spread: 'Germination and hyphal penetration of the stratum corneum and hair follicles. Does not invade living tissue.',
      organs: [ 'Skin', 'Hair follicles', 'Claws/Nails' ],
      lesions: 'Hyperkeratosis, parakeratosis, folliculitis, and resulting alopecia.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Cell-mediated immunity (Th1) is crucial for clearing the infection, causing the characteristic inflammatory ring. Humoral response is not protective.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Rapidly spreading circular areas of alopecia, erythema, scaling, and crusting. Often on face, ears, and forelimbs.',
        chronic: 'Thickened, hyperkeratotic, crusty lesions (especially T. verrucosum in calves).',
        subclinical: 'Common in adult cats, showing no visible lesions but shedding infectious spores.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Tinea corporis: Itchy, circular, erythematous, scaling lesions with central clearing. Tinea capitis (scalp) causes alopecia.',
        chronic: 'Nail infections (Tinea unguium) can be chronic and difficult to treat.',
        subclinical: 'Rare in humans.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Circular, well-circumscribed areas of hair loss, scaling, erythema, and sometimes exudation (kerion).',
    histopathology: 'Fungal hyphae and arthroconidia visible in the keratin layer and surrounding hair shafts (endothrix/ectothrix) using PAS or GMS stains.',
    sampleCollection: 'Skin scrapings from the active edge of the lesion, plucked hairs. Use a toothbrush technique for asymptomatic cats.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'Direct microscopy using 10% KOH (reveals hyphae/spores). Fungal culture on Dermatophyte Test Medium (DTM) is the gold standard.',
    rapidTests: "Wood's lamp examination (M. canis may fluoresce apple-green, but only ~50% of strains do).",
    serology: 'Not useful for diagnosis.',
    pcr: 'Real-time PCR on hair/scale samples is highly sensitive and provides rapid species identification.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Demodicosis, Staphylococcal pyoderma, Malassezia dermatitis, Pemphigus foliaceus, Flea allergy dermatitis.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Systemic antifungals combined with topical therapy and rigorous environmental decontamination.',
    drugResistance: 'Emerging resistance in some Trichophyton species, but still largely susceptible to standard azoles/allylamines.',
    vaccination: 'Vaccines exist for T. verrucosum in cattle and M. canis in cats, primarily for reducing clinical severity, not preventing infection.',
    biosecurity: 'Strict hygiene, isolation of infected animals, vacuuming to remove infected hair, disinfection with 1:10 bleach or enilconazole.',
    control: "Screening incoming animals (especially shelter cats) with Wood's lamp and DTM cultures.",
    prevention: 'Avoiding overcrowding, minimizing fomite sharing, maintaining good nutrition and husbandry.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Highly contagious zoonosis. M. canis from pets is a frequent cause of tinea in children.',
    onehealth: 'Requires simultaneous treatment of the pet, the human owners, and the household environment to break the cycle of reinfection.',
    economicImportance: 'Hide damage in cattle, loss of performance in racehorses, and significant costs for prolonged treatment in shelters/catteries.',
    indianContext: 'Highly prevalent in livestock and stray dogs/cats due to tropical climate and high humidity which favor fungal survival.',
    globalContext: 'Worldwide distribution. One of the most common zoonotic skin diseases globally.',
    recentAdvances: 'Widespread adoption of PCR panels has drastically reduced the diagnosis time from 2-3 weeks (culture) to 24 hours.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Ringworm is a contagious, superficial fungal infection causing circular alopecia, requiring combined patient and environmental treatment.',
    quickRevision: "Fungus, M. canis, T. verrucosum, Wood's lamp, DTM red color change, circular alopecia, highly zoonotic.",
    references: [ 'Merck Vet Manual', 'ESCCAP Guidelines on Dermatophytosis' ]
  },
  toxoplasmosis: {
    definition: 'Toxoplasmosis is a widespread zoonotic infection caused by the obligate intracellular protozoan Toxoplasma gondii, affecting all warm-blooded animals and humans, characterized primarily by abortion in sheep and neurological/congenital disease in humans.',
    historicalBackground: 'Discovered in 1908 in the gundi (a North African rodent) by Nicolle and Manceaux. Recognized as a major cause of congenital birth defects in humans in the 1930s.',
    etiology: 'Toxoplasma gondii. Exists in three infective stages: sporozoites (in oocysts), tachyzoites (rapidly multiplying), and bradyzoites (in tissue cysts).',
    taxonomy: 'Phylum Apicomplexa, Class Sporozoasida, Subclass Coccidiasina, Order Eucoccidiorida, Family Sarcocystidae.',
    morphology: 'Crescent-shaped tachyzoites (2x6 µm). Bradyzoites clustered in thin-walled tissue cysts (up to 100 µm). Unsporulated oocysts are spherical (10-12 µm); sporulated oocysts contain two sporocysts, each with four sporozoites.',
    hostRange: 'All warm-blooded animals (mammals and birds) act as intermediate hosts.',
    reservoir: 'Felids (cats) are the only definitive hosts (where sexual reproduction occurs).',
    vectors: 'Mechanical transmission of oocysts via flies/cockroaches is possible, but biological vectors do not exist.',
    carrierState: 'Latent tissue cysts (containing bradyzoites) persist in muscles and CNS of intermediate hosts for life.',
    envSurvival: 'Oocysts are extremely hardy, surviving in moist soil, water, and sandboxes for over 1-2 years. Resistant to standard disinfectants and freezing.',
    transmission: '1) Ingestion of sporulated oocysts from cat feces (soil/water). 2) Ingestion of tissue cysts in undercooked meat. 3) Transplacental (tachyzoites). 4) Unpasteurized milk.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Oral ingestion or transplacental.',
      spread: 'Excystation in the gut, invasion of intestinal epithelium, transformation into tachyzoites, systemic hematogenous/lymphatic dissemination, crossing placenta/BBB.',
      organs: [ 'Lymph nodes', 'Brain', 'Eye', 'Placenta', 'Skeletal muscle' ],
      lesions: 'Multifocal necrosis due to tachyzoite multiplication, leading to granulomatous inflammation.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Strong Th1-mediated response (IL-12, IFN-gamma, CD8+ T cells) forces tachyzoites to encyst into dormant bradyzoites, establishing lifelong latent infection.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: "Sheep/Goats: Usually asymptomatic except in pregnant naive ewes, causing abortion ('storm'), mummification, or stillbirths.",
        chronic: 'Rare. Neurological signs in immunocompromised dogs/cats.',
        subclinical: 'Most intermediate hosts and shedding cats show no clinical signs.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Mostly asymptomatic. Can cause mild flu-like illness with cervical lymphadenopathy.',
        chronic: 'Chorioretinitis (visual impairment), reactivation in HIV/AIDS causing fatal Toxoplasmic encephalitis (ring-enhancing brain lesions).',
        subclinical: 'Congenital: Hydrocephalus, chorioretinitis, intracranial calcifications (classic triad) if mother is infected during pregnancy.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: "Placenta (sheep): Cotyledons have 1-2mm white necrotic foci ('strawberry cotyledons'). Fetal brain: Leucomalacia.",
    histopathology: 'Non-suppurative encephalitis, retinitis, and placentitis. Free tachyzoites and intact tissue cysts visible with H&E, IHC, or PAS.',
    sampleCollection: 'Placental cotyledons, fetal brain, maternal serum. Adult serum.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'Histopathology/IHC of aborted material. Serology (IgG/IgM) is primary in humans/pets.',
    rapidTests: 'Latex agglutination, lateral flow assays for feline and human serology.',
    serology: 'Sabin-Feldman Dye Test (gold standard, human), ELISA, IFAT. Paired titers needed to show active infection.',
    pcr: 'Real-time PCR on amniotic fluid (humans) or fetal tissues (animals).',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Abortion in sheep: Campylobacter, Chlamydia (Enzootic abortion), Brucella, Q Fever. Encephalitis: Neospora caninum.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Pyrimethamine + Sulfadiazine + Folinic acid (to prevent bone marrow toxicity). Clindamycin in cats/dogs.',
    drugResistance: 'Not a major clinical issue, but treatment only kills tachyzoites, not encysted bradyzoites.',
    vaccination: 'Toxovax (live attenuated S48 strain) for sheep to prevent abortion. No human or cat vaccine.',
    biosecurity: 'Pregnant women should avoid cleaning litter boxes. Do not feed cats raw meat.',
    control: 'Daily cleaning of cat litter (oocysts take 1-5 days to sporulate and become infectious). Cook meat to >66°C.',
    prevention: 'Washing vegetables, washing hands after gardening, freezing meat at -20°C for 2 days to kill cysts.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Major foodborne and congenital pathogen. One of the leading causes of death attributed to foodborne illness in the US.',
    onehealth: 'Perfectly illustrates the interface of companion animals (cats), food safety (undercooked meat/milk), and human vulnerability (pregnancy/immunosuppression).',
    economicImportance: 'Major cause of ovine abortion globally, leading to significant agricultural losses.',
    indianContext: 'High seroprevalence in human population. Commonly transmitted via contaminated water and unwashed vegetables due to large stray cat populations.',
    globalContext: 'Estimated 1/3 of the global human population is chronically infected.',
    recentAdvances: "Research into targeted inhibitors of the parasite's apicoplast and bump-hole kinase inhibitors.",
    keyTakeHome: 'Cat definitive host, sheep abortion, human congenital triad (hydrocephalus), foodborne (undercooked meat) or environmental (oocyst) transmission.',
    quickRevision: 'T. gondii, cats, oocysts, tissue cysts, sheep abortion, strawberry cotyledons, congenital triad, pyrimethamine.',
    references: [ 'WOAH Terrestrial Manual', 'CDC Toxoplasmosis' ]
  },
  bse: {
    definition: "Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy (BSE), commonly known as 'Mad Cow Disease', is a fatal, progressive, neurodegenerative disease of cattle.",
    historicalBackground: 'First recognized in the UK in 1986. The epidemic peaked in 1992, traced to meat-and-bone meal contaminated with prions.',
    etiology: 'Prion (PrP^Sc), an abnormally folded, protease-resistant isoform of the normal cellular prion protein (PrP^C).',
    taxonomy: 'Not applicable (non-viral, non-bacterial proteinaceous infectious particle).',
    morphology: 'Misfolded beta-sheet rich protein aggregates forming amyloid fibrils in the brain.',
    hostRange: 'Primarily cattle. Can be transmitted experimentally to other species.',
    reservoir: 'Infected cattle.',
    vectors: 'None.',
    carrierState: 'Long preclinical incubation period (2-8 years) where animals are infectious but asymptomatic.',
    envSurvival: 'Extremely resistant to heat, UV light, ionizing radiation, and standard chemical disinfectants.',
    transmission: 'Ingestion of feed contaminated with the infectious prion agent (e.g., meat-and-bone meal).',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Ingestion and absorption across the intestinal mucosa.',
      spread: "Replication in Peyer's patches, ascension via sympathetic and parasympathetic nerves to the spinal cord and brain.",
      organs: [ 'Brain', 'Spinal cord', 'Retina', 'Ileum (distal)' ],
      lesions: 'Spongiform vacuolation of gray matter neuropil, neuronal degeneration, astrocytosis, without inflammatory response.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'No detectable humoral or cellular immune response, as the agent is a modified host protein.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Not applicable (chronic progressive disease).',
        chronic: 'Apprehension, hyperesthesia to sound/touch, ataxia, tremors, falling, weight loss, decreased milk production.',
        subclinical: 'Animals remain asymptomatic during the long incubation period.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Not applicable.',
        chronic: 'Variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (vCJD): Psychiatric symptoms (depression, anxiety), painful sensory symptoms, followed by ataxia, dementia, and death.',
        subclinical: 'Long incubation period; blood transfusions from asymptomatic carriers can transmit vCJD.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'No specific gross lesions observed.',
    histopathology: 'Bilateral, symmetrical spongiform changes (vacuoles) in neurons and neuropil, particularly in the brainstem. Amyloid plaques may be seen.',
    sampleCollection: 'Brainstem (obex) from dead cattle. Strict biosecurity required.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'Post-mortem testing of brain tissue. No validated live-animal test.',
    rapidTests: 'ELISA, Lateral Flow Assays on obex tissue.',
    serology: 'Not applicable (no antibodies produced).',
    pcr: 'Not applicable (no nucleic acid).',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Rabies, Listeriosis, Lead poisoning, Hypomagnesemia (Grass tetany), Ketosis.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'No treatment. Disease is uniformly fatal.',
    drugResistance: 'Not applicable.',
    vaccination: 'No vaccine available.',
    biosecurity: 'Incineration or alkaline hydrolysis of carcasses at high temperatures/pressures.',
    control: 'Ban on feeding mammalian protein to ruminants (Ruminant Feed Ban). Active surveillance programs.',
    prevention: 'Removal of Specified Risk Materials (SRMs) like brain, spinal cord, from the human food chain.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Causal agent of variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (vCJD) in humans, an untreatable and universally fatal neurodegenerative condition.',
    onehealth: 'A classic example of agricultural practices (feed manufacturing) directly causing a major human public health crisis, necessitating coordinated global veterinary and medical responses.',
    economicImportance: 'Caused massive economic losses globally due to trade embargoes, culling of millions of cattle, and implementation of costly surveillance.',
    indianContext: 'India is historically free from BSE. Strict import controls and ban on meat-and-bone meal in ruminant feed maintain this status.',
    globalContext: 'Stringent global regulations (OIE/WOAH standards) have brought cases to near zero worldwide.',
    recentAdvances: 'Development of Protein Misfolding Cyclic Amplification (PMCA) and Real-Time Quaking-Induced Conversion (RT-QuIC) for ultra-sensitive prion detection.',
    keyTakeHome: 'BSE is a fatal, feed-borne prion disease of cattle linked to human vCJD, controlled strictly by feed bans and SRM removal.',
    quickRevision: 'Prion, feed-borne, neurodegeneration, vCJD, obex, spongiform change, feed ban, universally fatal.',
    references: [
      'WOAH Terrestrial Manual',
      'Merck Veterinary Manual',
      'WHO guidelines on TSEs'
    ]
  },
  salmonellosis: {
    definition: 'Salmonellosis is a highly prevalent foodborne zoonotic disease caused by non-typhoidal Salmonella species, leading to acute gastroenteritis in humans and varied systemic diseases in animals.',
    historicalBackground: 'Named after Daniel Elmer Salmon. S. Enteritidis emerged as a major global pandemic strain linked to poultry eggs in the 1980s.',
    etiology: 'Salmonella enterica. Over 2,600 serovars. Gram-negative, facultative anaerobic, motile bacilli.',
    taxonomy: 'Phylum Pseudomonadota, Class Gammaproteobacteria, Order Enterobacterales, Family Enterobacteriaceae.',
    morphology: 'Medium-sized Gram-negative rods with peritrichous flagella.',
    hostRange: 'All vertebrates. Poultry, Pigs, Cattle, Reptiles (frequent carriers).',
    reservoir: 'Intestinal tract of domestic and wild animals. Reptiles (turtles, iguanas).',
    vectors: 'Mechanical transmission by rodents, flies.',
    carrierState: 'Crucial. Animals (especially poultry and reptiles) often carry and shed the bacteria asymptomatically in feces for life.',
    envSurvival: 'Highly resilient. Survives for months in soil, water, and dried feces. Multiplies in unrefrigerated food.',
    transmission: 'Humans: Consumption of contaminated food (raw eggs, undercooked poultry/pork, unpasteurized milk). Contact with reptiles. Animals: Fecal-oral.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Oral ingestion.',
      spread: "Bacteria invade the intestinal epithelium (M cells) via a Type III Secretion System (T3SS), triggering massive cytoskeletal rearrangement ('membrane ruffling'). Multiplies in macrophages.",
      organs: [
        'Intestines',
        'Mesenteric lymph nodes',
        'Gallbladder (carrier state)'
      ],
      lesions: 'Fibrinonecrotic enteritis, mucosal ulceration.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Neutrophil infiltration causes massive inflammation and fluid secretion (diarrhea). Secretory IgA is protective.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Calves/Piglets: Fever, severe foul-smelling watery/bloody diarrhea, septicemia, death. Poultry: Fowl Typhoid/Pullorum (highly fatal in chicks).',
        chronic: 'Failure to thrive, intermittent diarrhea.',
        subclinical: 'Most adult poultry and swine are asymptomatic carriers (major food safety risk).'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Non-typhoidal: Nausea, vomiting, abdominal cramps, bloody diarrhea, fever lasting 4-7 days.',
        chronic: "Reactive arthritis (Reiter's syndrome) months later.",
        subclinical: 'Asymptomatic shedding occurs.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: "Fibrinous/diphtheritic enteritis ('button ulcers' in pigs), enlarged mesenteric lymph nodes, focal hepatic necrosis.",
    histopathology: 'Necrotizing enteritis, microabscesses in the liver (paratyphoid nodules).',
    sampleCollection: 'Feces, cloacal swabs, feed samples, tissue at necropsy.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'Culture on selective media (XLD agar, MacConkey). Biochemical testing.',
    rapidTests: 'PCR-based screening of food products/flocks.',
    serology: 'Agglutination tests for specific serovars (e.g., Pullorum testing in poultry).',
    pcr: 'Real-time PCR for rapid detection in food matrices and veterinary diagnostics.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'E. coli (ETEC/EHEC), Campylobacter, Clostridium perfringens, Rotavirus, Coccidiosis.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Uncomplicated cases: Fluid therapy (antibiotics contraindicated as they prolong shedding). Severe/Septicemic cases: Cephalosporins or Fluoroquinolones.',
    drugResistance: 'Massive global issue. Multi-Drug Resistant (MDR) strains (e.g., S. Typhimurium DT104) are prevalent due to agricultural antibiotic abuse.',
    vaccination: 'Poultry: Live attenuated and inactivated vaccines widely used for S. Enteritidis to prevent egg contamination.',
    biosecurity: 'Rodent control, strict hygiene, all-in-all-out farming, feed sterilization.',
    control: 'Routine testing and culling of breeder flocks for specific serovars.',
    prevention: 'Cooking eggs/meat thoroughly. Handwashing after touching reptiles.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'One of the most common causes of foodborne diarrheal disease and food recalls worldwide.',
    onehealth: 'Requires farm-to-fork intervention: vaccinating chickens, enforcing abattoir hygiene, and educating consumers on kitchen practices.',
    economicImportance: 'Billions of dollars lost annually in healthcare, food recalls, and productivity.',
    indianContext: 'Endemic. Poor sanitation and unhygienic meat processing contribute to high human incidence.',
    globalContext: 'Global prevalence. S. Enteritidis dominates in poultry; S. Typhimurium dominates in pigs.',
    recentAdvances: 'Widespread use of Whole Genome Sequencing (WGS) to rapidly trace the origin of foodborne outbreaks back to specific farms.',
    keyTakeHome: "Fecal-oral foodborne pathogen. Invades enterocytes. Poultry and reptiles are major asymptomatic carriers. Don't use antibiotics for mild diarrhea.",
    quickRevision: 'S. enterica, membrane ruffling, T3SS, poultry eggs, reptiles, fibrinonecrotic enteritis, MDR, foodborne.',
    references: [ 'CDC Salmonella', 'FDA Bad Bug Book' ]
  },
  plague: {
    definition: 'Plague is an acute, fulminating, and highly lethal zoonotic bacterial disease caused by Yersinia pestis, characterized by bubonic, septicemic, or pneumonic forms.',
    historicalBackground: 'Caused three major pandemics: Justinian Plague (541 AD), The Black Death (1347 - killed 1/3 of Europe), and the Third Pandemic (1855 - China/India).',
    etiology: 'Yersinia pestis. Gram-negative, facultative anaerobic, bipolar-staining coccobacillus.',
    taxonomy: 'Family Yersiniaceae, Genus Yersinia. Evolved recently from Y. pseudotuberculosis by acquiring specific plasmids.',
    morphology: 'Pleomorphic, safety-pin appearance (bipolar staining) with Giemsa/Wayson stain.',
    hostRange: 'Rodents (primary reservoir). Humans, Cats (highly susceptible). Dogs (resistant).',
    reservoir: 'Wild rodents (prairie dogs, ground squirrels, marmots) maintain the sylvatic cycle. Rats (Rattus rattus) drive the urban cycle.',
    vectors: 'Fleas, primarily Xenopsylla cheopis (Oriental rat flea).',
    carrierState: 'Enzootic cycles in resistant wild rodents.',
    envSurvival: 'Can survive in soil/carcasses for weeks in cold conditions, but readily destroyed by sunlight/heat.',
    transmission: "1) Flea bite (flea's gut is blocked by Y. pestis biofilm, causing it to regurgitate bacteria while feeding). 2) Handling infected animal tissues (hunters/vets). 3) Aerosol (cat-to-human or human-to-human pneumonic plague).",
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Skin (flea bite) or respiratory tract.',
      spread: 'Phagocytosed by macrophages at the bite site, travels to regional lymph node, survives and multiplies intracellularly using a Type III Secretion System (Yops) that destroys macrophage function. Leads to massive hemorrhagic lymphadenitis (bubo) and septicemia.',
      organs: [ 'Lymph nodes', 'Blood', 'Lungs', 'Spleen' ],
      lesions: 'Severe hemorrhagic and necrotic lymphadenitis, disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC).'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'The bacteria paralyze the innate immune system (Yops inhibit phagocytosis and cytokine production), allowing massive unhindered replication.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Cats: Severe fever, anorexia, hugely enlarged submandibular lymph nodes, pneumonia, rapid death. Dogs: Usually asymptomatic or mild fever.',
        chronic: 'Rare.',
        subclinical: 'Wild rodent reservoirs.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: "Bubonic: High fever, exquisitely painful, swollen lymph node (bubo) in groin/axilla. Septicemic: Septic shock, gangrene of extremities ('Black Death'). Pneumonic: Rapidly fatal pneumonia, coughing blood.",
        chronic: 'Not applicable.',
        subclinical: 'Rare.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Massive hemorrhagic and necrotic lymph nodes. Petechiae and ecchymoses throughout viscera. Consolidation and hemorrhage in lungs (pneumonic).',
    histopathology: 'Obliteration of lymph node architecture by massive hemorrhage, necrosis, and sheets of extracellular bacteria.',
    sampleCollection: 'Bubo aspirate, blood, sputum. Extreme biohazard (BSL-3).',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: "Wayson/Giemsa stain showing bipolar 'safety-pin' bacilli. Culture on blood agar.",
    rapidTests: 'F1 antigen rapid dipstick test is crucial during outbreaks in remote areas.',
    serology: 'Passive hemagglutination targeting the F1 capsular antigen.',
    pcr: 'Real-time PCR for rapid confirmation.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Tularemia, Anthrax, Scrub Typhus, severe Staphylococcal/Streptococcal adenitis.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Must be started immediately. Streptomycin, Gentamicin, Doxycycline, or Ciprofloxacin.',
    drugResistance: 'Naturally rare, but engineered multi-drug resistant weaponized strains are a theoretical bioterrorism threat.',
    vaccination: 'Killed whole-cell vaccines existed but are no longer widely used due to severe side effects and poor protection against pneumonic plague.',
    biosecurity: 'Strict barrier nursing, N95 masks for pneumonic cases. Avoid handling sick cats without PPE.',
    control: 'Flea control (insecticides) MUST precede rodent control (rodenticides), otherwise starving fleas will bite humans.',
    prevention: 'Flea control on pets. Avoiding wild rodents (prairie dogs) in endemic areas.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Category A bioterrorism agent. A re-emerging disease causing localized outbreaks (e.g., Madagascar).',
    onehealth: 'Requires balancing wildlife conservation (prairie dogs) with public health interventions and domestic pet management.',
    economicImportance: 'Historical cause of societal collapse. Today, localized economic impacts during outbreaks.',
    indianContext: 'Historically caused massive mortality. A significant outbreak occurred in Surat in 1994, causing nationwide panic. Currently exists in quiet sylvatic foci in the Himalayas.',
    globalContext: 'Endemic in Madagascar (regular large outbreaks), DRC, and the Western USA (Four Corners).',
    recentAdvances: 'Improved understanding of the Yersinia Type III Secretion System has paved the way for novel targeted therapeutics.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Flea-borne from rodents. Causes painful buboes or fatal pneumonia. Cats are highly susceptible and can transmit pneumonic plague to humans.',
    quickRevision: 'Y. pestis, Xenopsylla, safety-pin stain, bubo, blocked flea, pneumonic, cats, Streptomycin, Black Death.',
    references: [ 'WHO Plague', 'CDC Plague' ]
  },
  qfever: {
    definition: "Q Fever ('Query' Fever) is a highly infectious, ubiquitous zoonotic disease caused by the obligate intracellular bacterium Coxiella burnetii, typically causing abortion in ruminants and a flu-like illness or atypical pneumonia in humans.",
    historicalBackground: 'Described in 1937 by Edward Holbrook Derrick in abattoir workers in Queensland, Australia. The causative agent was identified by Macfarlane Burnet.',
    etiology: 'Coxiella burnetii. Small, pleomorphic, obligate intracellular Gram-negative bacterium.',
    taxonomy: 'Phylum Pseudomonadota, Class Gammaproteobacteria, Order Legionellales, Family Coxiellaceae.',
    morphology: 'Exhibits a biphasic life cycle: Large Cell Variant (LCV) which is metabolically active inside host cells, and Small Cell Variant (SCV) which acts as a spore-like form in the environment.',
    hostRange: 'Sheep, Goats, Cattle, Cats, Dogs, Ticks. Humans.',
    reservoir: 'Domestic ruminants (especially sheep and goats).',
    vectors: 'Ticks maintain the sylvatic cycle, but are not required for domestic transmission.',
    carrierState: 'Infected ruminants shed the bacteria chronically in milk, urine, feces, and massive quantities in birth products.',
    envSurvival: 'The SCV is incredibly robust, surviving for months in soil, dust, and wool. Highly resistant to heat, drying, and many disinfectants.',
    transmission: 'Inhalation of aerosolized bacteria from contaminated dust (especially near lambing/kidding areas). Ingestion of unpasteurized milk. Tick bites (rare in humans).',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Inhalation into the lungs.',
      spread: 'Phagocytosed by alveolar macrophages. Unique among pathogens, it actively requires the acidic environment of the phagolysosome (pH 4.5) to multiply. Disseminates to placenta, liver, and spleen.',
      organs: [ 'Placenta', 'Lungs', 'Liver', 'Heart valves (Humans)' ],
      lesions: 'Severe necrotizing placentitis in ruminants.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Phase variation of LPS determines virulence (Phase I is virulent and hides from immunity; Phase II is avirulent). Requires strong T-cell immunity to clear.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Often asymptomatic. May cause late-term abortion, stillbirths, or delivery of weak offspring, particularly in sheep and goats. Cattle usually only show infertility.',
        chronic: 'Subclinical shedding in subsequent pregnancies.',
        subclinical: 'The most common presentation.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Self-limiting flu-like illness, severe headache, atypical pneumonia, or hepatitis.',
        chronic: 'Endocarditis (mostly in patients with pre-existing valvular defects), occurring years after initial infection. Chronic fatigue syndrome.',
        subclinical: 'Approximately 50% of human infections are asymptomatic.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Placenta is thickened, leathery, and covered in a greyish-white exudate. Intercotyledonary areas are severely affected.',
    histopathology: 'Necrotizing placentitis. Trophoblasts are packed with massive numbers of basophilic, intracellular bacteria (visible with Modified Ziehl-Neelsen).',
    sampleCollection: 'Aborted placenta, fetal stomach contents, vaginal swabs, milk.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: "Smears of placental cotyledons stained with Stamp's (MZN) showing masses of red coccobacilli.",
    rapidTests: 'None routine for field use.',
    serology: 'ELISA is widely used for herd screening. IFA (distinguishing Phase I and Phase II antibodies) is used for staging human disease.',
    pcr: 'Real-time PCR on placenta, milk, or vaginal swabs.',
    differentialDiagnosis: "Animals: Brucellosis, Chlamydia (Enzootic Abortion), Toxoplasmosis, Campylobacter. Humans: Legionnaires' disease, Mycoplasma pneumonia, Brucellosis.",
    treatmentPrinciples: "Animals: Oxytetracycline during late pregnancy may reduce abortion risk, but doesn't eliminate shedding. Humans: Doxycycline (acute); Doxycycline + Hydroxychloroquine (chronic endocarditis) for >18 months.",
    drugResistance: 'Not a major issue, though the intracellular acidic niche makes drug penetration difficult.',
    vaccination: 'Animals: Inactivated Phase I vaccines (e.g., Coxevac) used in Europe. Humans: Q-Vax (Australia only) used for abattoir workers (requires pre-screening to avoid severe local reactions).',
    biosecurity: 'Wear N95 respirators when handling aborting ruminants or cleaning barns. Proper disposal of placentas.',
    control: 'Isolating aborting animals. Composting manure properly before spreading on fields.',
    prevention: 'Pasteurization of milk. Vaccination of high-risk workers.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Highly infectious (infectious dose is <10 bacteria). Major occupational hazard. Caused the massive 2007-2010 Dutch outbreak linked to dairy goat farms.',
    onehealth: 'Windborne spread from goat farms into urban areas demonstrates that agricultural zoning is a critical public health tool.',
    economicImportance: 'Loss of offspring and milk production. Occupational health costs.',
    indianContext: 'Endemic, but vastly underdiagnosed due to lack of diagnostic facilities. Often causes undifferentiated fevers.',
    globalContext: 'Worldwide distribution (except New Zealand).',
    recentAdvances: 'The massive Netherlands outbreak spurred the development of better environmental surveillance tools (air sampling) and mandatory goat vaccination policies.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Tick/aerosol transmitted intracellular bacteria causing abortion in goats/sheep and pneumonia/endocarditis in humans. Highly infectious spore-like form.',
    quickRevision: 'Coxiella, aerosol, goats/sheep, Phase I/II, atypical pneumonia, endocarditis, acidic phagolysosome, Q-Vax.',
    references: [ 'WOAH Q Fever', 'CDC Q Fever' ]
  },
  listeriosis: {
    definition: 'Listeriosis is a severe foodborne zoonosis and animal disease caused by Listeria monocytogenes, leading to encephalitis and abortion in ruminants, and meningitis/septicemia in immunocompromised humans.',
    historicalBackground: 'Identified by Murray, Webb, and Swann in 1926 from laboratory rabbits. Recognized as a major foodborne pathogen in the 1980s.',
    etiology: 'Listeria monocytogenes. Gram-positive, non-spore-forming, facultative anaerobic, motile rod.',
    taxonomy: 'Phylum Bacillota, Class Bacilli, Order Bacillales, Family Listeriaceae.',
    morphology: "Short Gram-positive rods with characteristic 'tumbling motility' at room temperature (25°C) but non-motile at 37°C.",
    hostRange: 'Ruminants (sheep, cattle, goats). Humans.',
    reservoir: 'Soil, decaying vegetation, poorly fermented silage (pH > 5.0).',
    vectors: 'None.',
    carrierState: 'Animals and humans can shed the bacteria asymptomatically in feces.',
    envSurvival: 'Psychrotrophic (multiplies at refrigerator temperatures, 4°C). Highly resistant to freezing, drying, and high salt concentrations.',
    transmission: 'Animals: Ingestion of contaminated, spoiled silage. Humans: Ingestion of contaminated ready-to-eat foods (deli meats, soft cheeses, unpasteurized dairy).',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Oral ingestion or entry via mucosal abrasions in the mouth.',
      spread: "Internalin A/B facilitate entry into enterocytes/macrophages. Listeriolysin O (LLO) allows escape from the phagosome. Actin-based motility ('comet tails') pushes the bacteria directly into adjacent cells, evading antibodies. Tropism for the brainstem and placenta.",
      organs: [ 'Brainstem (Animals)', 'Placenta', 'Meninges (Humans)' ],
      lesions: 'Microabscesses in the brainstem, severe necrotizing placentitis.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Strictly reliant on Cell-Mediated Immunity (CD8+ T-cells, macrophages). Pregnant women and neonates have reduced CMI, hence their extreme susceptibility.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: "Encephalitic form ('Circling Disease'): Unilateral facial paralysis (drooping ear/lip), head tilt, circling, dysphagia, profound depression. Reproductive form: Late-term abortion, stillbirths. Septicemic form: Sudden death in neonates.",
        chronic: 'Rare.',
        subclinical: 'Fecal shedding.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Gastroenteritis (healthy adults). In immunocompromised/elderly: Severe meningoencephalitis, septicemia. In pregnant women: Mild flu-like illness resulting in devastating abortion, stillbirth, or neonatal granulomatosis infantiseptica.',
        chronic: 'Not applicable.',
        subclinical: 'Frequent.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Brain usually looks grossly normal, possibly some meningeal congestion. Aborted fetuses show pinpoint yellow foci of necrosis in the liver.',
    histopathology: 'Brainstem: Severe localized microabscesses and perivascular cuffing (mononuclear cells). Liver: Focal necrosis.',
    sampleCollection: 'Brainstem (medulla/pons), aborted fetus, placenta, silage samples. Human CSF/Blood.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: "Culture on selective media (e.g., PALCAM, Oxford agar) with 'Cold Enrichment' (incubating at 4°C for weeks) improving recovery.",
    rapidTests: 'PCR/ELISA widely used for rapid food safety screening.',
    serology: 'Not useful.',
    pcr: 'Real-time PCR for rapid definitive diagnosis in food and clinical samples.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Animals: Rabies, BSE, Polioencephalomalacia, Lead poisoning, Pregnancy toxemia. Humans: Group B Strep (neonates), E. coli meningitis.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Animals: High doses of Penicillin or Ampicillin (must penetrate the BBB). Humans: Ampicillin + Gentamicin.',
    drugResistance: 'Generally susceptible, but intrinsic resistance to cephalosporins is a key clinical feature.',
    vaccination: 'None routinely available or effective.',
    biosecurity: 'Proper silage management (ensure anaerobic conditions and rapid pH drop below 4.5).',
    control: 'Discarding spoiled silage. Isolating aborting animals.',
    prevention: 'For pregnant/immunocompromised humans: strictly avoid soft cheeses, deli meats, and unpasteurized dairy. Reheat hot dogs to steaming.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Causes the highest hospitalization and mortality rates (20-30%) among foodborne illnesses.',
    onehealth: 'Requires rigorous food safety inspection standards and zero-tolerance policies for L. monocytogenes in ready-to-eat foods.',
    economicImportance: 'Massive economic impacts from food recalls and lawsuits.',
    indianContext: 'Increasingly recognized as a food safety threat with the rise of processed and ready-to-eat foods in urban centers.',
    globalContext: 'Major concern in developed nations relying heavily on refrigerated supply chains.',
    recentAdvances: 'Use of bacteriophages as an FDA-approved food additive to spray on deli meats to kill Listeria.',
    keyTakeHome: "Grows in the fridge. Causes 'circling disease' in sheep fed bad silage. Causes abortion and meningitis in humans via deli meats/soft cheese. Actin comet tails.",
    quickRevision: 'Psychrotroph, bad silage, circling disease, brainstem microabscesses, soft cheese, actin rockets, Ampicillin, cephalosporin-resistant.',
    references: [ 'FDA Bad Bug Book', 'WOAH Listeriosis' ]
  },
  glanders: {
    definition: 'Glanders is a highly contagious, chronic and often fatal zoonotic disease primarily affecting equines, characterized by ulcerating nodules in the respiratory tract and skin, caused by Burkholderia mallei.',
    historicalBackground: 'Known since antiquity (described by Hippocrates). Used as one of the first biological weapons in World War I (targeting Allied cavalry and transport horses).',
    etiology: 'Burkholderia mallei. Gram-negative, non-motile, obligate mammalian pathogen.',
    taxonomy: 'Phylum Pseudomonadota, Class Betaproteobacteria, Order Burkholderiales, Family Burkholderiaceae.',
    morphology: 'Slender, Gram-negative rod.',
    hostRange: 'Horses (chronic), Mules and Donkeys (acute/fatal). Humans, Carnivores (if they eat infected meat).',
    reservoir: 'Infected equines (chronically infected carrier horses).',
    vectors: 'None.',
    carrierState: "Chronically infected 'occult' carrier horses are the main source of infection.",
    envSurvival: 'Obligate parasite. Cannot survive long outside the host, unlike its soil-dwelling cousin B. pseudomallei.',
    transmission: 'Ingestion of contaminated food/water (shared troughs). Inhalation of respiratory secretions. Direct contact with skin exudates. Humans infected via occupational contact.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Oral or respiratory route, or via skin abrasions.',
      spread: 'Spreads via lymphatics and blood. Forms granulomatous nodules that rapidly undergo caseous necrosis and ulceration.',
      organs: [ 'Lungs', 'Nasal mucosa', 'Skin/Lymphatics' ],
      lesions: "Nodules, ulcers, and star-shaped scars in the nasal septum. Cord-like thickened lymphatics ('Farcy')."
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Causes intense granulomatous inflammation but the bacteria evade clearance, leading to chronic debilitating disease.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Donkeys/Mules: High fever, severe respiratory distress, rapid death.',
        chronic: "Horses: Three forms (often overlapping). 1) Nasal form: Ulcers on the nasal septum exuding thick, yellowish-green pus. 2) Pulmonary form: Chronic cough, unthriftiness, nodules in lungs. 3) Cutaneous form ('Farcy'): Nodules along thickened lymphatic vessels that rupture and drain pus.",
        subclinical: 'Occult carriers.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Localized ulcer at the site of entry, progressing to severe pneumonia, septicemia, and disseminated abscesses. Highly fatal if untreated.',
        chronic: 'Multiple abscesses in muscles, liver, and spleen.',
        subclinical: 'Rare.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: "Nasal septum: Punched-out ulcers healing with characteristic stellate (star-shaped) scars. Lungs: Miliary nodules resembling TB. Skin: 'Farcy pipes' (thickened lymphatics).",
    histopathology: 'Granulomatous nodules with central necrosis, surrounded by epithelioid cells and giant cells.',
    sampleCollection: 'Nasal swabs, pus from Farcy lesions, blood. Extreme biohazard (BSL-3).',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'Culture and identification.',
    rapidTests: 'Mallein test (historical, analogous to the tuberculin test, injected intra-palpebrally).',
    serology: 'Complement Fixation Test (CFT) is the prescribed test for international trade.',
    pcr: 'Real-time PCR for rapid, safe diagnosis.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Equine: Strangles (Streptococcus equi), Epizootic Lymphangitis (Histoplasma farciminosum), Ulcerative Lymphangitis (Corynebacterium pseudotuberculosis), Melioidosis.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Equines: Treatment is strictly prohibited by law in most countries (positive animals MUST be euthanized). Humans: Prolonged intensive antibiotics (Ceftazidime, Imipenem, Doxycycline).',
    drugResistance: 'Naturally resistant to many antibiotics.',
    vaccination: 'None available.',
    biosecurity: 'Immediate quarantine. Euthanasia and deep burial/incineration of infected animals. Disinfection of stables.',
    control: 'Strict import testing (CFT). Test-and-slaughter policy is universally enforced.',
    prevention: 'Elimination of the disease in equines protects humans.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Category B bioterrorism agent. A severe occupational hazard for equine vets and laboratory workers.',
    onehealth: 'Requires strict veterinary surveillance and border controls to prevent re-introduction into disease-free countries.',
    economicImportance: 'Massive trade implications. Outbreaks shut down international movement of horses.',
    indianContext: 'Endemic. Sporadic outbreaks occur, particularly among working equines (tongas, brick kilns) in North India, prompting localized quarantines.',
    globalContext: 'Eradicated from North America and Western Europe. Endemic in parts of Asia, Middle East, and South America.',
    recentAdvances: 'Development of improved recombinant antigen ELISAs to replace the cumbersome CFT.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Equine disease causing nasal ulcers (star-shaped scars) and skin nodules (Farcy). Highly zoonotic, treatment prohibited in horses.',
    quickRevision: 'B. mallei, horses, Farcy pipes, stellate scars, mallein test, test-and-slaughter, bioterrorism.',
    references: [ 'WOAH Glanders' ]
  },
  campylobacteriosis: {
    definition: 'Campylobacteriosis is a leading cause of bacterial gastroenteritis worldwide, primarily caused by Campylobacter jejuni, transmitted largely through undercooked poultry.',
    historicalBackground: 'Identified in 1886 by Theodor Escherich. Originally thought to be a Vibrio, recognized as a major human pathogen in the 1970s following the development of selective microaerophilic culture techniques.',
    etiology: 'Campylobacter jejuni (majority of human cases), C. coli (pigs), C. fetus (reproductive disease in cattle/sheep). Gram-negative, microaerophilic, spirally curved rods.',
    taxonomy: 'Phylum Pseudomonadota, Class Epsilonproteobacteria, Order Campylobacterales, Family Campylobacteraceae.',
    morphology: "Curved, S-shaped, or 'seagull-winged' Gram-negative rods. Highly motile with a single polar flagellum (darting motility).",
    hostRange: 'Poultry (universal carriers), Cattle, Sheep, Pigs, Dogs, Cats. Humans.',
    reservoir: 'Avian species (poultry and wild birds). The high body temperature of birds (41°C) perfectly suits C. jejuni.',
    vectors: 'Mechanical transmission by flies.',
    carrierState: 'Commercial poultry flocks are universally colonized asymptomatically.',
    envSurvival: 'Fragile in the environment. Sensitive to drying, oxygen, and freezing. Requires microaerophilic conditions (5% O2, 10% CO2).',
    transmission: 'Humans: Consumption of undercooked poultry, cross-contamination in the kitchen, unpasteurized milk. Pets: Fecal-oral.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Oral ingestion.',
      spread: 'Motility allows penetration of intestinal mucus. Adheres to and invades enterocytes, producing Cytolethal Distending Toxin (CDT) which causes cell cycle arrest and DNA damage.',
      organs: [ 'Jejunum', 'Ileum', 'Colon' ],
      lesions: 'Acute exudative enteritis with mucosal ulceration.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Local IgA limits infection. In rare cases, cross-reactivity between Campylobacter lipooligosaccharides (LOS) and human nerve gangliosides triggers Guillain-Barré Syndrome.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'C. jejuni: Usually asymptomatic in poultry. Can cause diarrhea in puppies/kittens. C. fetus: Causes late-term abortion and infertility in cattle and sheep.',
        chronic: 'None.',
        subclinical: 'Universal in poultry.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Profuse, watery, often bloody diarrhea, severe abdominal cramping (mimicking appendicitis), fever, lasting 3-5 days.',
        chronic: 'Post-infectious sequelae: Guillain-Barré Syndrome (GBS - acute flaccid paralysis) and Reactive Arthritis.',
        subclinical: 'Frequent.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Hyperemic, edematous intestinal mucosa with hemorrhage.',
    histopathology: 'Acute neutrophilic infiltration of the lamina propria, crypt abscesses.',
    sampleCollection: 'Fresh feces (transported in specialized medium like Cary-Blair).',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: "Culture on selective media (e.g., Campy-BAP, Skirrow's) incubated at 42°C under microaerophilic conditions.",
    rapidTests: 'Rapid antigen detection (EIA) on stool.',
    serology: 'Not useful clinically.',
    pcr: 'Multiplex PCR gastrointestinal panels have largely replaced culture in human medicine.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Salmonella, Shigella, E. coli O157:H7, Yersinia enterocolitica.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Usually self-limiting; requires only fluid therapy. If severe (bloody/high fever): Macrolides (Azithromycin) are first-line.',
    drugResistance: 'Increasing resistance to Fluoroquinolones (Ciprofloxacin) linked to veterinary use of enrofloxacin in poultry.',
    vaccination: 'C. fetus vaccines used in cattle/sheep. No vaccine for C. jejuni in poultry or humans.',
    biosecurity: 'Strict farm biosecurity to delay colonization of broiler flocks.',
    control: 'Improved abattoir hygiene (scald water pH, chilling).',
    prevention: 'Thorough cooking of poultry. Strict kitchen hygiene (avoid washing raw chicken to prevent aerosolization).',
    publicHealthImportance: 'The most common bacterial cause of human gastroenteritis in many developed countries. Leading trigger for GBS.',
    onehealth: 'Highlights the direct link between veterinary antibiotic use (fluoroquinolones in poultry) and resistant human infections.',
    economicImportance: 'Massive burden of lost work days and GBS rehabilitation.',
    indianContext: 'Highly prevalent but underreported due to fastidious culture requirements. Rampant fluoroquinolone resistance.',
    globalContext: 'Worldwide.',
    recentAdvances: 'Development of bacteriophage therapy to reduce C. jejuni loads in the ceca of broiler chickens pre-slaughter.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Seagull-winged bacteria. Number one cause of foodborne diarrhea (via raw chicken). Triggers Guillain-Barré Syndrome. Requires microaerophilic culture at 42°C.',
    quickRevision: 'C. jejuni, seagull-wing, darting motility, undercooked poultry, Guillain-Barre, microaerophilic, Azithromycin.',
    references: [ 'WHO Campylobacter', 'FDA Bad Bug Book' ]
  },
  pasteurellosis: {
    definition: 'Pasteurellosis refers to a group of primarily respiratory and septicemic diseases caused by Pasteurella multocida, including Bovine Respiratory Disease, Fowl Cholera, and severe human wound infections from animal bites.',
    historicalBackground: 'Pasteur isolated the bacterium from birds (Fowl Cholera) in 1880, using it to demonstrate the principle of live-attenuated vaccination.',
    etiology: 'Pasteurella multocida. Gram-negative, non-motile, facultative anaerobic coccobacillus. Classified by capsular types (A, B, D, E, F).',
    taxonomy: 'Phylum Pseudomonadota, Class Gammaproteobacteria, Order Pasteurellales, Family Pasteurellaceae.',
    morphology: "Small Gram-negative coccobacilli. Exhibits characteristic bipolar staining (safety-pin appearance) with Giemsa or Wright's stain.",
    hostRange: 'Cattle (Bovine Respiratory Disease, Hemorrhagic Septicemia), Pigs (Atrophic Rhinitis), Poultry (Fowl Cholera), Rabbits (Snuffles), Dogs/Cats (oral flora).',
    reservoir: 'Upper respiratory tract and oral cavity of healthy domestic animals.',
    vectors: 'None.',
    carrierState: 'Extremely common. Acts as an opportunistic pathogen triggered by stress.',
    envSurvival: 'Poor survival in the environment. Relies on animal-to-animal transmission.',
    transmission: 'Animals: Aerosol, direct contact, or stress-induced endogenous overgrowth. Humans: Bites or scratches from cats and dogs.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Respiratory tract or skin wounds.',
      spread: 'In animals: Viral infection or stress impairs mucociliary clearance, allowing P. multocida to descend into the lungs causing fibrinous pneumonia. Type B/E strains cause fulminant Hemorrhagic Septicemia. Type D (with Bordetella) causes osteolytic toxins in pigs. In humans: Rapid local tissue invasion and cellulitis.',
      organs: [ 'Lungs', 'Skin/Subcutis (Humans)', 'Nasal turbinates (Pigs)' ],
      lesions: 'Fibrinous bronchopneumonia, severe cellulitis, bone resorption.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Capsule provides resistance to phagocytosis. Specific immunity requires antibodies directed against capsular and somatic antigens.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: "Bovines (BRD): Fever, cough, nasal discharge, dyspnea. Bovines (HS): Sudden onset high fever, profuse salivation, severe submandibular edema, rapid death. Poultry (Fowl Cholera): Sudden death, swollen cyanotic wattles. Rabbits: Purulent nasal discharge ('snuffles').",
        chronic: 'Pigs (Atrophic Rhinitis): Snorting, epistaxis, severe deviation/shortening of the snout.',
        subclinical: 'Upper respiratory carriers.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Rapid onset (within 24 hours) of intense pain, erythema, and swelling at the site of a cat/dog bite. Can progress to tenosynovitis or osteomyelitis.',
        chronic: 'Rare.',
        subclinical: 'Not applicable.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Cattle (BRD): Cranioventral consolidation of the lungs with fibrinous pleuritis. Pigs: Complete destruction of nasal turbinates.',
    histopathology: 'Severe fibrinosuppurative bronchopneumonia. Oat cells (elongated macrophages) are classic.',
    sampleCollection: 'Nasal/deep tracheal swabs, lung tissue, bite wound exudate.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'Culture on Blood Agar (does NOT grow on MacConkey). Has a distinctive sweet, musty odor.',
    rapidTests: 'None routine.',
    serology: 'Not useful clinically.',
    pcr: 'Multiplex PCR for capsular typing and toxin gene detection.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Cattle (BRD): Mannheimia haemolytica, Histophilus somni. Poultry: HPAI, Newcastle Disease. Humans: Capnocytophaga canimorsus, Bartonella, Staphylococcus.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Animals: Macrolides, Florfenicol, Tetracyclines. Humans: Amoxicillin-Clavulanate (Augmentin) is the drug of choice for animal bites.',
    drugResistance: 'Increasing antimicrobial resistance in bovine respiratory isolates due to mass medication.',
    vaccination: 'Animals: Widely used. Hemorrhagic Septicemia alum/oil adjuvant vaccines. Toxoid vaccines for Atrophic Rhinitis. Live-attenuated for Fowl Cholera.',
    biosecurity: 'Minimizing stress (overcrowding, transport, poor ventilation).',
    control: 'Pre-conditioning calves before feedlot entry.',
    prevention: 'Prompt, aggressive cleaning and antibiotic prophylaxis of cat bites in humans.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'The most common pathogen isolated from dog and cat bites, requiring immediate medical attention to prevent permanent joint/tendon damage.',
    onehealth: 'Highlights the microbiome of companion animals as a direct acute threat to humans via bites.',
    economicImportance: 'Bovine Respiratory Disease (Shipping Fever) is the most economically devastating disease of the beef industry globally.',
    indianContext: 'Hemorrhagic Septicemia (Type B:2) is highly endemic and causes massive mortality in cattle and buffaloes during the monsoon season.',
    globalContext: 'HS is restricted to Asia and Africa. BRD and Fowl Cholera are worldwide.',
    recentAdvances: 'Development of markerless gene-deletion mutant vaccines providing superior mucosal immunity in cattle.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Opportunistic pathogen causing shipping fever in cattle, fowl cholera, and severe rapid cellulitis after cat bites. Augmentin for bites.',
    quickRevision: 'P. multocida, bipolar staining, shipping fever, fowl cholera, atrophic rhinitis, cat bite, cellulitis, Augmentin.',
    references: [ 'Merck Vet Manual', 'WOAH Hemorrhagic Septicemia' ]
  },
  melioidosis: {
    definition: "Melioidosis (Whitmore's Disease) is a severe, glanders-like zoonotic and environmental disease caused by the soil saprophyte Burkholderia pseudomallei, affecting humans and multiple animal species in tropical regions.",
    historicalBackground: 'Described by Alfred Whitmore in 1912 in morphia addicts in Rangoon, Burma.',
    etiology: 'Burkholderia pseudomallei. Gram-negative, motile, aerobic, non-spore-forming bacillus.',
    taxonomy: 'Phylum Pseudomonadota, Class Betaproteobacteria, Order Burkholderiales, Family Burkholderiaceae.',
    morphology: 'Bipolar staining (safety-pin appearance). Highly motile.',
    hostRange: 'Humans, Sheep, Goats, Pigs, Horses, Dogs. (Practically all mammals).',
    reservoir: 'Wet soil and stagnant water (especially rice paddies). It is a true environmental saprophyte.',
    vectors: 'None.',
    carrierState: 'Can remain latent in humans and animals for decades before reactivation.',
    envSurvival: 'Thrives in moist, acidic clay soils and muddy water in the tropics. Can survive for years.',
    transmission: 'Percutaneous inoculation (working bare-foot in rice paddies), inhalation (during heavy rains/typhoons), or ingestion of contaminated water. Zoonotic (animal-to-human) transmission is extremely rare; both acquire it from the environment.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Skin abrasions, lungs, GI tract.',
      spread: 'Intracellular pathogen capable of surviving in macrophages. Spreads hematogenously causing disseminated microabscesses in virtually any organ.',
      organs: [ 'Lungs', 'Liver', 'Spleen', 'Prostate', 'Skin' ],
      lesions: 'Abscesses that may coalesce into large suppurative necrotic masses.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Requires a robust cell-mediated immune response. Diabetes is the major risk factor for severe disease, as it impairs neutrophil/macrophage function.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Septicemia and rapid death, especially in sheep and goats.',
        chronic: 'Multiple abscesses in lungs, spleen, joints, and CNS. Chronic emaciation.',
        subclinical: 'Latent infections.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: "Highly variable ('The Great Imitator'). Acute pulmonary infection (mimicking TB), severe septicemia, or localized skin abscesses.",
        chronic: 'Chronic suppurative infection lasting months.',
        subclinical: "Latent infection that can reactivate years later (termed the 'Vietnamese Time Bomb' in US veterans)."
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Caseous or purulent abscesses in lungs, liver, spleen, and lymph nodes. Indistinguishable from Glanders or TB grossly.',
    histopathology: 'Suppurative to pyogranulomatous inflammation with prominent necrosis.',
    sampleCollection: 'Pus, blood, sputum, soil samples. Must be handled in BSL-3.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: "Culture on Ashdown's agar (colonies have a characteristic wrinkled, metallic appearance and an earthy smell).",
    rapidTests: 'Lateral flow assays targeting capsular polysaccharides are used in endemic settings.',
    serology: 'IHA (Indirect Hemagglutination) used but limited by high background seropositivity in endemic areas.',
    pcr: 'Real-time PCR for rapid diagnosis.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Tuberculosis, Glanders, Brucellosis, Staphylococcal abscesses, Systemic mycoses.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Extremely difficult to treat. Requires intensive IV therapy (Ceftazidime or Meropenem) for 2-4 weeks, followed by eradication oral therapy (TMP-SMX) for 3-6 months to prevent relapse.',
    drugResistance: 'Intrinsically resistant to many antibiotics (penicillins, macrolides, aminoglycosides).',
    vaccination: 'None available for humans or animals.',
    biosecurity: 'Standard precautions.',
    control: 'Culling of infected animals.',
    prevention: 'Wearing waterproof boots/gloves when working in wet soil (rice farmers). Providing chlorinated drinking water.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Major neglected tropical disease. High mortality rate (up to 40%) even with treatment. Tier 1 Select Agent (bioterrorism threat).',
    onehealth: 'Disease incidence is directly tied to extreme weather events (monsoons, cyclones) which aerosolize the bacteria and bring it to the soil surface.',
    economicImportance: 'Significant burden on agricultural workers in Southeast Asia.',
    indianContext: 'Highly endemic along the western coast (Karnataka, Kerala) and Tamil Nadu. Often triggered by the monsoon.',
    globalContext: 'Highly endemic in Southeast Asia (Thailand) and Northern Australia. Increasingly recognized globally.',
    recentAdvances: 'Mapping of global environmental suitability highlighting massive underreporting in Africa and South America.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Soil/water saprophyte. Infects rice farmers and diabetics. Causes severe abscesses mimicking TB. Needs prolonged Ceftazidime + TMP-SMX.',
    quickRevision: "B. pseudomallei, soil/water, rice farmers, diabetes, Great Imitator, Ashdown's agar, Ceftazidime, Vietnamese time bomb.",
    references: [ 'CDC Melioidosis' ]
  },
  jencephalitis: {
    definition: 'Japanese Encephalitis (JE) is a mosquito-borne zoonotic viral disease causing reproductive failure in pigs and severe viral encephalitis in humans.',
    historicalBackground: 'First recorded outbreak in Japan in 1871. Virus isolated in 1935.',
    etiology: 'Japanese Encephalitis Virus (JEV). Enveloped, positive-sense single-stranded RNA virus.',
    taxonomy: 'Family Flaviviridae, Genus Flavivirus. Closely related to West Nile, St. Louis Encephalitis, and Dengue.',
    morphology: 'Spherical virion (50 nm) with an envelope containing the E glycoprotein.',
    hostRange: 'Pigs (major amplifying host), Ardeid birds (wading birds/herons/egrets - reservoir), Horses (dead-end host), Humans (dead-end host).',
    reservoir: 'Aquatic wading birds (herons, egrets).',
    vectors: 'Culex mosquitoes (primarily Culex tritaeniorhynchus, which breed in flooded rice paddies).',
    carrierState: 'Pigs experience rapid, high-titer viremia allowing mosquito infection, but clear the virus rapidly.',
    envSurvival: 'Fragile outside the host. Requires continuous mosquito-vertebrate-mosquito cycling.',
    transmission: 'Bite of infected Culex mosquitoes.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Mosquito bite.',
      spread: 'Replication in local lymph nodes, viremia. In pigs, virus crosses the placenta to infect the fetus. In horses/humans, virus may cross the blood-brain barrier causing encephalitis.',
      organs: [
        'Brain (Humans/Horses)',
        'Placenta/Fetus (Pigs)',
        'Testes (Boars)'
      ],
      lesions: 'Fetal mummification (pigs). Non-suppurative encephalomyelitis (humans/horses).'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Strong neutralizing antibody response usually clears viremia before CNS invasion in most infected humans/horses.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Pigs: Usually asymptomatic except for pregnant sows (abortion storms, mummified fetuses, stillbirths, weak piglets) and boars (orchitis/infertility). Horses: Fever, lethargy, rarely fatal encephalitis.',
        chronic: 'Reproductive failure in swine herds.',
        subclinical: 'Most adult pigs and horses are asymptomatic.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Vast majority (99%) are asymptomatic. Severe cases: Acute onset of high fever, headache, neck stiffness, disorientation, seizures (especially in children), spastic paralysis, coma. 30% mortality in symptomatic cases.',
        chronic: '30-50% of survivors suffer permanent neuropsychiatric sequelae.',
        subclinical: 'Very common (1 symptomatic case per 250 infections).'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Pigs: Mummified, malformed fetuses; subcutaneous edema of fetus. Humans: Brain congestion and edema.',
    histopathology: 'Perivascular cuffing, neuronal necrosis, neuronophagia, and microglial nodules in the thalamus, basal ganglia, and brainstem.',
    sampleCollection: 'Pigs: Aborted fetuses (brain, spleen). Humans: CSF and serum.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'Detection of JEV-specific IgM in CSF (diagnostic for CNS infection) or serum.',
    rapidTests: 'IgM capture ELISA (MAC-ELISA) on CSF is the gold standard point-of-care equivalent.',
    serology: 'MAC-ELISA, Plaque Reduction Neutralization Test (PRNT) to rule out cross-reactivity with Dengue/West Nile.',
    pcr: 'RT-PCR on CSF or fetal tissue.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Pigs: PRRS, Parvovirus, PCV2, Pseudorabies, Brucellosis. Humans: Nipah, Rabies, Herpes simplex encephalitis, Cerebral malaria.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Supportive care. No specific antivirals.',
    drugResistance: 'Not applicable.',
    vaccination: 'Humans: Highly effective vaccines available (live-attenuated SA 14-14-2, inactivated Vero cell). Pigs: Vaccination used to prevent abortion and reduce amplification.',
    biosecurity: 'Mosquito control around piggeries.',
    control: 'Moving pig farms away from human settlements (Singapore strategy). Vector control.',
    prevention: 'Routine vaccination of children in endemic regions. Use of mosquito nets and repellents.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'The leading cause of viral encephalitis in Asia, with ~68,000 cases annually.',
    onehealth: 'The classic ecological triad: Rice paddies (mosquito breeding) + Wading birds (reservoir) + Pigs (amplifier) + Humans (incidental victim).',
    economicImportance: 'Significant losses in swine breeding operations due to reproductive failure.',
    indianContext: 'Highly endemic in Uttar Pradesh (Gorakhpur), Assam, and West Bengal. Major cause of pediatric encephalitis outbreaks.',
    globalContext: 'Endemic across South, Southeast, and East Asia.',
    recentAdvances: 'Widespread integration of the SA 14-14-2 vaccine into national childhood immunization programs has drastically reduced incidence.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Mosquito-borne flavivirus. Causes abortion/mummification in pigs (amplifiers) and severe encephalitis in children (dead-end hosts).',
    quickRevision: 'Flavivirus, Culex, pigs amplifier, wading birds, abortion storms, pediatric encephalitis, MAC-ELISA, SA 14-14-2.',
    references: [ 'WHO Japanese Encephalitis', 'OIE Terrestrial Manual' ]
  },
  rift_valley: {
    definition: 'Rift Valley Fever (RVF) is an acute, mosquito-borne viral zoonosis affecting ruminants (causing massive abortion storms and high neonatal mortality) and humans (causing flu-like illness, hemorrhagic fever, or encephalitis).',
    historicalBackground: 'First identified in 1931 during an epidemic among sheep on a farm in the Rift Valley of Kenya.',
    etiology: 'Rift Valley Fever Virus (RVFV). Enveloped, negative-sense, segmented (L, M, S) single-stranded RNA virus.',
    taxonomy: 'Order Bunyavirales, Family Phenuiviridae, Genus Phlebovirus.',
    morphology: 'Spherical virion (80-120 nm) with glycoprotein spikes.',
    hostRange: 'Sheep, Cattle, Goats, Camels (highly susceptible). Humans.',
    reservoir: 'Aedes mosquitoes (transovarial transmission allows the virus to survive in dormant mosquito eggs in dry soil for years).',
    vectors: 'Aedes spp. (primary maintenance and amplifying vectors) and Culex spp. (secondary epidemic vectors).',
    carrierState: 'No vertebrate carrier state. Maintained in mosquito eggs.',
    envSurvival: "Virus survives in dormant Aedes eggs in 'dambos' (depressions) during dry periods, hatching en masse during heavy rains (e.g., El Niño).",
    transmission: 'Animals: Mosquito bites. Humans: Direct contact with blood/fluids of infected animals (slaughter, veterinary care, assisting birth) OR mosquito bites.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Mosquito bite or mucosal/percutaneous exposure.',
      spread: 'Viremia, targeting the liver (causing severe acute hepatic necrosis) and crossing the placenta (causing fetal death).',
      organs: [ 'Liver', 'Placenta/Fetus', 'Spleen', 'Brain (rare)' ],
      lesions: 'Massive acute hepatic necrosis.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Strong neutralizing antibodies provide lifelong immunity after recovery.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: "Neonatal lambs/calves: High fever, weakness, 90-100% mortality within 2-3 days. Pregnant adults: 'Abortion storms' (up to 100% abortion rate), fever, agalactia, jaundice.",
        chronic: 'None.',
        subclinical: 'Adult indigenous breeds often have mild or subclinical disease.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Usually self-limiting flu-like illness. Severe cases (1-2%): Ocular disease (retinitis, blindness), Meningoencephalitis, or Hemorrhagic Fever (jaundice, hematemesis, 50% mortality).',
        chronic: 'Permanent visual impairment in ocular form.',
        subclinical: 'Many infections are asymptomatic.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Liver is enlarged, yellow/friable, with scattered petechiae and massive focal necrosis. Extensive hemorrhage in serosal surfaces.',
    histopathology: 'Severe centrilobular to panlobular hepatic necrosis with eosinophilic intranuclear inclusion bodies.',
    sampleCollection: 'Blood/Serum during febrile phase. Aborted fetuses (liver/spleen). Must be handled with extreme care (BSL-3/4).',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'RT-PCR, Virus Isolation, or ELISA for IgM/IgG.',
    rapidTests: 'Penside lateral flow assays available for herd screening during outbreaks.',
    serology: 'IgM ELISA confirms recent infection.',
    pcr: 'RT-PCR is fast, highly sensitive, and safer than virus isolation.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Animals: Bluetongue, Wesselsbron disease, Brucellosis, Q fever, Anthrax. Humans: Malaria, Dengue, Ebola, CCHF.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Supportive care. No approved specific antivirals.',
    drugResistance: 'Not applicable.',
    vaccination: 'Animals: Live attenuated (Smithburn strain - can cause abortion in pregnant animals, Clone 13) and Inactivated vaccines. Humans: Investigational vaccines only.',
    biosecurity: 'PPE (gloves, masks, goggles) essential for veterinarians and abattoir workers handling suspected cases.',
    control: 'Animal vaccination PRIOR to the rainy season. Restricting animal movement during outbreaks.',
    prevention: 'Vector control (larvicides). Forecasting outbreaks using satellite imagery (tracking El Niño rainfall anomalies).',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Major occupational hazard for veterinarians, farmers, and butchers. Potential for international spread via infected animal trade.',
    onehealth: 'Perfect example of climate-driven zoonosis. Satellite prediction of rainfall anomalies (ENSO) allows proactive animal vaccination to prevent human epidemics.',
    economicImportance: 'Catastrophic livestock losses and severe trade embargoes on exporting countries.',
    indianContext: 'Not present in India. Strict quarantine on livestock imports from Africa/Middle East maintains freedom.',
    globalContext: 'Endemic to Sub-Saharan Africa. Has spread to Egypt, Madagascar, and the Arabian Peninsula.',
    recentAdvances: 'Climate-based early warning systems (FAO/WHO) successfully predicting outbreaks months in advance.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Mosquito-borne Bunyavirus linked to heavy rains. Causes 100% abortion in sheep and hemorrhagic fever in humans handling aborted materials.',
    quickRevision: 'Phlebovirus, Aedes eggs, El Nino, abortion storms, liver necrosis, hemorrhagic fever, occupational hazard.',
    references: [ 'OIE Terrestrial Manual', 'WHO RVF' ]
  },
  influenza: {
    definition: 'Avian Influenza (AI) is a highly contagious viral disease of birds. Highly Pathogenic Avian Influenza (HPAI) causes devastating mortality in poultry and poses a severe pandemic threat to humans via zoonotic spillover.',
    historicalBackground: "First described in Italy in 1878 as 'fowl plague'. The 1997 H5N1 outbreak in Hong Kong marked the first time an avian influenza virus caused severe human respiratory disease directly from birds.",
    etiology: 'Avian Influenza A virus. Enveloped, negative-sense, single-stranded, segmented (8 segments) RNA virus.',
    taxonomy: 'Family Orthomyxoviridae, Genus Alphainfluenzavirus.',
    morphology: 'Pleomorphic or spherical virion (80-120 nm). Surface glycoproteins Hemagglutinin (HA) for entry and Neuraminidase (NA) for release dictate the subtype (e.g., H5N1, H7N9).',
    hostRange: 'Wild waterfowl (natural reservoir), Domestic poultry (chickens, turkeys), Swine, Humans.',
    reservoir: 'Wild aquatic birds (Anseriformes and Charadriiformes) maintain Low Pathogenic (LPAI) strains asymptomatically.',
    vectors: 'None.',
    carrierState: "Wild birds shed LPAI continuously. Pigs can act as 'mixing vessels' for avian, swine, and human strains.",
    envSurvival: 'Survives for weeks in cold water/feces. Sensitive to heat, desiccation, and lipid solvents.',
    transmission: 'Direct contact with infected bird feces, respiratory secretions, or contaminated fomites/water. Humans infected via direct contact with sick/dead poultry (e.g., live bird markets).',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Inhalation or ingestion.',
      spread: 'LPAI replicates locally in the respiratory/GI tract. HPAI strains (possessing a multi-basic cleavage site in the HA protein) are cleaved by ubiquitous host proteases, allowing systemic replication in endothelium and multiple organs.',
      organs: [ 'Respiratory tract', 'Endothelium', 'Brain', 'Liver' ],
      lesions: 'Severe pulmonary edema, systemic hemorrhage, necrosis.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Humoral response against HA is protective but highly strain-specific. Antigenic drift (point mutations) and shift (reassortment) constantly evade population immunity.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'HPAI in Poultry: Sudden death (up to 100% flock mortality within 48h) without prior signs. Edema of the head/wattles, cyanosis of combs, petechial hemorrhages on shanks, drop in egg production.',
        chronic: 'Not applicable.',
        subclinical: 'Wild birds with LPAI.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'H5N1: Rapid progression to severe viral pneumonia, ARDS, multiorgan failure. High mortality (>50%).',
        chronic: 'Not applicable.',
        subclinical: 'Rare with HPAI strains.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Poultry: Subcutaneous hemorrhage on legs, cyanotic comb/wattles, severe tracheitis, pinpoint hemorrhages on epicardium and proventriculus.',
    histopathology: 'Necrotizing bronchitis, severe pulmonary edema, diffuse endothelial damage with hemorrhages.',
    sampleCollection: 'Cloacal and tracheal swabs from poultry. Serum. Tissue samples.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'Viral isolation in embryonated chicken eggs or RT-PCR. HA/NA subtyping.',
    rapidTests: 'Rapid antigen tests (lateral flow) available but lack sensitivity for early detection.',
    serology: 'Hemagglutination Inhibition (HI) test, Agar Gel Immunodiffusion (AGID).',
    pcr: 'Real-time RT-PCR targeting the Matrix gene (for Influenza A), followed by H5/H7 specific primers.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Newcastle Disease (clinically indistinguishable from HPAI), Fowl Cholera, Infectious Laryngotracheitis.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Poultry: None (stamping out). Humans: Neuraminidase inhibitors (Oseltamivir/Tamiflu) if administered early.',
    drugResistance: 'Resistance to adamantanes is widespread; NA inhibitor resistance occurs sporadically.',
    vaccination: 'Used in poultry in endemic countries (China, Egypt) but complicates serological surveillance (DIVA strategy required). Human prepandemic vaccines stockpiled.',
    biosecurity: 'Stringent biosecurity on commercial poultry farms to prevent contact with wild birds (nets, closed housing).',
    control: "Rapid culling ('stamping out') of infected and exposed flocks. Movement restrictions.",
    prevention: 'Closing live bird markets during outbreaks. Surveillance of wild bird flyways.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'HPAI H5N1 is considered the pathogen with the highest potential to cause a devastating global human pandemic if it acquires sustained human-to-human transmissibility.',
    onehealth: 'Requires integration of wild bird ecology (flyway tracking), agricultural practices (live markets), and human pandemic preparedness.',
    economicImportance: 'Billions of dollars lost due to mass culling of commercial poultry and international trade bans.',
    indianContext: 'Frequent outbreaks of H5N1 and H5N8 in poultry and wild birds, managed aggressively by culling. No human cases reported yet.',
    globalContext: 'Ongoing panzootic of H5N1 clade 2.3.4.4b affecting birds and mammals (including dairy cattle in the US) globally.',
    recentAdvances: 'The recent spillover of HPAI H5N1 into dairy cattle in the US, highlighting the unpredictable host-range expansion of the virus.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Segmented RNA virus capable of antigenic shift. Causes sudden death in poultry. Massive pandemic threat requiring strict biosecurity and culling.',
    quickRevision: 'Orthomyxovirus, HA/NA spikes, multi-basic cleavage site, wild waterfowl, stamping out, ARDS, pandemic threat.',
    references: [ 'WHO Avian Influenza', 'WOAH Terrestrial Manual' ]
  },
  hendravirus: {
    definition: 'Hendra virus (HeV) is a highly fatal zoonotic paramyxovirus transmitted from flying foxes to horses, and subsequently from horses to humans.',
    historicalBackground: 'Emerged in 1994 in Hendra, a suburb of Brisbane, Australia, causing a fatal outbreak in a racing stable (killing 14 horses and a trainer).',
    etiology: 'Hendra virus. Enveloped, single-stranded negative-sense RNA virus.',
    taxonomy: 'Order Mononegavirales, Family Paramyxoviridae, Genus Henipavirus.',
    morphology: 'Pleomorphic, enveloped virions with surface glycoproteins.',
    hostRange: 'Pteropid fruit bats (flying foxes) act as reservoirs. Horses (amplifying hosts). Humans (dead-end hosts). Dogs have rarely been infected.',
    reservoir: 'Flying foxes (Pteropus species).',
    vectors: 'None.',
    carrierState: 'Bats shed virus asymptomatically in urine, feces, and saliva.',
    envSurvival: 'Fragile in the environment, easily destroyed by heat and desiccation.',
    transmission: 'Horses ingest pasture/water contaminated by bat urine or masticated fruit. Humans are infected via close contact with infected horses (respiratory secretions/blood). NO bat-to-human or human-to-human transmission has been recorded.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Oronasal exposure.',
      spread: 'Viremia leads to widespread infection of endothelial cells, causing systemic vasculitis, thrombosis, and ischemia in lungs and brain.',
      organs: [ 'Lungs', 'Brain', 'Blood vessels' ],
      lesions: 'Severe interstitial pneumonia, pulmonary edema, non-suppurative encephalitis.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Inflammatory cascade and cytokine storm contribute to lung pathology.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Horses: Sudden onset of high fever, frothy/blood-stained nasal discharge, severe respiratory distress, neurological signs (ataxia, head pressing), rapid death (mortality >75%).',
        chronic: 'Not applicable.',
        subclinical: 'Extremely rare in horses.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Influenza-like illness progressing rapidly to severe pneumonia and/or encephalitis. High case fatality rate (>50%).',
        chronic: 'Late-onset or relapsing encephalitis can occur.',
        subclinical: 'Rare.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Horses: Heavy, congested, edematous lungs with copious frothy fluid in the trachea. Dilated subpleural lymphatics.',
    histopathology: 'Fibrinoid necrosis of blood vessels, syncytial cells in the vascular endothelium, pulmonary edema.',
    sampleCollection: 'Blood, nasal/oral swabs from horses (requires high biosecurity). Tissue samples at necropsy.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'RT-PCR on swabs or blood.',
    rapidTests: 'None routine.',
    serology: 'ELISA, Virus Neutralization Test (VNT).',
    pcr: 'Real-time RT-PCR is the primary diagnostic tool.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Equine Influenza, African Horse Sickness, Equine Herpesvirus-1, Equine Infectious Anemia, Snakebite, Plant toxicity.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Horses: Euthanasia due to extreme zoonotic risk. Humans: Intensive supportive care. Monoclonal antibody (m102.4) post-exposure.',
    drugResistance: 'Not applicable.',
    vaccination: 'Equivac HeV (a recombinant subunit vaccine based on the G protein) is available and highly effective for horses. Vaccinating horses breaks the transmission chain to humans.',
    biosecurity: 'Extreme biosecurity (PPE, N95 respirators) mandatory for veterinarians examining sick horses in endemic areas.',
    control: 'Strict quarantine of affected properties. Euthanasia of positive horses.',
    prevention: 'Vaccination of horses. Removing horse feed/water from under fruiting trees where bats roost.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Major occupational hazard for equine veterinarians and horse handlers in Australia.',
    onehealth: 'Highlights the necessity of veterinary vaccination (horses) to protect human public health, coupled with managing wildlife (bat) ecology.',
    economicImportance: 'Significant impact on the equine racing and breeding industry in Australia.',
    indianContext: 'Not reported in India, though the related Nipah virus is endemic.',
    globalContext: 'Currently restricted to the East coast of Australia.',
    recentAdvances: 'The successful deployment of the equine Hendra vaccine is a landmark achievement in One Health interventions.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Bat-to-Horse-to-Human transmission. Causes severe fatal pneumonia/encephalitis. Prevented entirely by vaccinating horses.',
    quickRevision: 'Henipavirus, flying foxes, Australia, frothy nasal discharge, syncytial cells, Equivac HeV, occupational hazard.',
    references: [ 'Australian Dept of Agriculture HeV Guidelines' ]
  },
  monkeypox: {
    definition: 'Mpox (formerly Monkeypox) is a zoonotic viral disease causing a smallpox-like illness, primarily endemic in Central and West Africa, but increasingly causing global outbreaks.',
    historicalBackground: 'First discovered in 1958 in laboratory monkeys (hence the name). First human case identified in 1970 in the DRC.',
    etiology: 'Monkeypox virus (MPXV). Large, enveloped, double-stranded DNA virus.',
    taxonomy: 'Family Poxviridae, Subfamily Chordopoxvirinae, Genus Orthopoxvirus (related to Smallpox and Cowpox).',
    morphology: 'Brick-shaped or ovoid virion (200-250 nm), highly complex structure with a core and lateral bodies.',
    hostRange: 'Rodents (primary reservoir), non-human primates, humans.',
    reservoir: 'African rodents (e.g., rope squirrels, Gambian pouched rats). Monkeys are incidental hosts.',
    vectors: 'None.',
    carrierState: 'Rodents can carry the virus asymptomatically.',
    envSurvival: 'Poxviruses are extremely resistant to drying and can survive for months in the environment, especially in scabs or clothing.',
    transmission: 'Zoonotic: Direct contact with blood/fluids of infected animals, or bites/scratches. Human-to-human: Close skin-to-skin contact, respiratory droplets, or fomites (bedding).',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Broken skin, respiratory tract, or mucous membranes.',
      spread: 'Primary replication in lymphoid tissue, followed by primary viremia. Secondary viremia leads to focal infection of the skin and mucosal surfaces.',
      organs: [ 'Skin', 'Lymph nodes', 'Mucous membranes' ],
      lesions: 'Progressive rash: macules -> papules -> vesicles -> pustules -> umbilication -> scabbing and scarring.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Cell-mediated and humoral immunity both play roles. Cross-immunity exists with other orthopoxviruses (e.g., smallpox vaccine provides cross-protection).',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Primates/Rodents: Fever, conjunctivitis, generalized pox-like rash (pustules).',
        chronic: 'Not applicable.',
        subclinical: 'Rodent reservoirs often show no signs.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Prodrome of fever, severe headache, and prominent lymphadenopathy (key differentiator from smallpox). Followed by the classic progressive pustular rash, often starting on the face or anogenital region.',
        chronic: 'Scars may remain permanently.',
        subclinical: 'Rare, mostly symptomatic.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Deep-seated, firm, well-circumscribed, umbilicated pustules on the skin and mucous membranes.',
    histopathology: 'Epidermal hyperplasia, ballooning degeneration of keratinocytes, prominent intracytoplasmic eosinophilic inclusion bodies (Guarnieri bodies).',
    sampleCollection: 'Swab of vesicle/pustule fluid or crusts (scabs).',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'PCR is the gold standard.',
    rapidTests: 'Orthopoxvirus antigen detection available but not MPXV specific.',
    serology: 'Orthopoxvirus IgM/IgG cross-reacts, limiting specificity.',
    pcr: 'Real-time PCR on lesion swabs provides rapid and definitive diagnosis.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Chickenpox (Varicella), Syphilis, Measles, Smallpox (eradicated), Cowpox.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Supportive care. Antiviral Tecovirimat (TPOXX) used for severe cases.',
    drugResistance: 'Emerging resistance to Tecovirimat noted in some strains.',
    vaccination: 'JYNNEOS (Modified Vaccinia Ankara - MVA) vaccine is approved and highly effective for pre- and post-exposure prophylaxis.',
    biosecurity: 'Standard, contact, and droplet precautions. Proper sterilization of fomites.',
    control: 'Isolating human cases, tracing contacts. In animals, quarantine of imported exotic pets.',
    prevention: 'Avoiding contact with wild rodents/primates in endemic areas. Vaccination of high-risk human groups.',
    publicHealthImportance: "The 2022 global outbreak demonstrated the virus's ability to establish sustained human-to-human transmission outside Africa.",
    onehealth: 'The 2003 US outbreak was caused by importing infected Gambian pouched rats which transmitted the virus to domestic prairie dogs, highlighting the risks of the exotic pet trade.',
    economicImportance: 'Significant impact on global public health resources and the exotic pet industry.',
    indianContext: 'Isolated imported human cases reported, successfully contained. Not endemic in Indian wildlife.',
    globalContext: 'Clade I (Congo Basin) is highly virulent. Clade II (West African) drove the 2022 global multi-country outbreak.',
    recentAdvances: 'Rapid mobilization of the JYNNEOS vaccine successfully curtailed the 2022 global epidemic.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Orthopoxvirus causing umbilicated pustules and lymphadenopathy. Rodent reservoir. Prevented by smallpox-derived vaccines.',
    quickRevision: 'Poxvirus, African rodents, lymphadenopathy, umbilicated pustules, exotic pet trade, Tecovirimat, JYNNEOS.',
    references: [ 'WHO Mpox', 'CDC Mpox' ]
  },
  hantavirus: {
    definition: 'Hantaviruses are rodent-borne viruses causing two major clinical syndromes in humans: Hemorrhagic Fever with Renal Syndrome (HFRS) in Eurasia, and Hantavirus Pulmonary Syndrome (HPS) in the Americas.',
    historicalBackground: 'HFRS recognized during the Korean War (Hantaan virus). HPS identified in 1993 following an outbreak of fatal respiratory illness in the Four Corners region of the USA (Sin Nombre virus).',
    etiology: 'Various Hantaviruses (e.g., Hantaan, Seoul, Puumala, Sin Nombre, Andes). Enveloped, negative-sense, tri-segmented RNA viruses.',
    taxonomy: 'Order Bunyavirales, Family Hantaviridae, Genus Orthohantavirus.',
    morphology: 'Spherical enveloped virions (80-120 nm).',
    hostRange: 'Rodents (reservoirs), Humans (dead-end hosts).',
    reservoir: 'Specific rodent species co-evolved with specific viruses (e.g., Deer mouse -> Sin Nombre; Brown rat -> Seoul).',
    vectors: 'None. Direct transmission from rodents.',
    carrierState: 'Rodents are chronically infected for life without showing clinical disease, shedding virus continuously.',
    envSurvival: 'Virus is relatively hardy, surviving in dried rodent excreta for days to weeks.',
    transmission: 'Inhalation of aerosolized virus from dried rodent urine, feces, or saliva (e.g., when sweeping a dusty cabin). Bite transmission is rare.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Inhalation into the respiratory tract.',
      spread: 'Infection of pulmonary or renal capillary endothelial cells. Does not cause direct cytopathology; instead, intense immune activation causes massive capillary leak.',
      organs: [ 'Lungs (HPS)', 'Kidneys (HFRS)', 'Endothelium' ],
      lesions: 'Severe non-cardiogenic pulmonary edema (HPS) or acute interstitial nephritis and hemorrhage (HFRS).'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Pathogenesis is largely immunopathological. CD8+ T-cells and cytokines drive vascular permeability.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'None. Rodents remain completely asymptomatic.',
        chronic: 'None.',
        subclinical: 'Lifelong persistent infection in the reservoir.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'HPS: Prodrome of fever/muscle aches, followed by sudden onset of severe dyspnea, hypoxia, and non-cardiogenic pulmonary edema. High mortality (35%). HFRS: Fever, hemorrhage, acute renal failure.',
        chronic: 'Survivors recover slowly but usually fully.',
        subclinical: 'Mild infections occur with some strains (e.g., Puumala virus).'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Humans (HPS): Lungs are heavy, edematous, and fluid-filled. Bilateral pleural effusions.',
    histopathology: 'Interstitial pneumonitis with mononuclear cell infiltrates and severe pulmonary edema. Viral antigen visible in endothelial cells via IHC.',
    sampleCollection: 'Serum (for antibodies). Post-mortem tissues.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'Serology is the primary diagnostic method.',
    rapidTests: 'Some commercial IgMs available.',
    serology: 'Detection of specific IgM or rising IgG via ELISA.',
    pcr: 'RT-PCR on blood or tissue during the acute phase.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'HPS: ARDS, Influenza, Pneumonic Plague, Anthrax. HFRS: Leptospirosis, Scrub Typhus.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'HPS: Intensive care, mechanical ventilation, ECMO. Extreme care with fluid resuscitation to avoid worsening pulmonary edema. No specific antivirals.',
    drugResistance: 'Not applicable.',
    vaccination: 'Vaccine for HFRS available in China/Korea (Hantaan/Seoul). No vaccine for HPS.',
    biosecurity: 'Wear N95 respirators when cleaning heavily rodent-infested areas.',
    control: 'Rodent control and exclusion from human dwellings.',
    prevention: 'Wet down rodent droppings with bleach before cleaning to prevent aerosolization. Do not dry sweep or vacuum.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'HPS is a rapidly fatal, emerging zoonosis across the Americas linked to fluctuating rodent populations.',
    onehealth: 'Disease outbreaks strongly correlate with environmental factors (e.g., heavy rainfall increasing food supply, leading to rodent population explosions).',
    economicImportance: 'Significant localized public health impacts during outbreaks.',
    indianContext: 'Seoul virus (transmitted by domestic rats) and Thottapalayam virus (shrews) are present, but major HPS outbreaks are not commonly recognized.',
    globalContext: 'HFRS dominates in Asia/Europe. HPS dominates in North/South America.',
    recentAdvances: 'Andes virus (South America) has demonstrated rare but confirmed human-to-human transmission, increasing its pandemic potential.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Rodent-borne virus transmitted via aerosolized urine/feces. Causes deadly pulmonary edema (Americas) or renal failure (Eurasia).',
    quickRevision: 'Bunyavirus, rodent urine, aerosol, HPS, HFRS, deer mouse, capillary leak, N95 respirator.',
    references: [ 'CDC Hantavirus' ]
  },
  creutzfeldt: {
    definition: 'Variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (vCJD) is a rare, fatal human neurodegenerative condition belonging to the transmissible spongiform encephalopathies (TSEs), caused by consumption of BSE-contaminated beef.',
    historicalBackground: 'Recognized in 1996 in the UK, definitively linked to the massive Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy (BSE) epizootic in British cattle.',
    etiology: 'Prion (PrP^Sc), specifically the BSE strain, an abnormally folded host protein.',
    taxonomy: 'Not a virus. Proteinaceous infectious particle.',
    morphology: 'Misfolded beta-sheet rich amyloid fibrils.',
    hostRange: 'Humans.',
    reservoir: 'BSE-infected cattle.',
    vectors: 'None.',
    carrierState: 'Decade-long incubation periods.',
    envSurvival: 'Highly resistant to sterilization.',
    transmission: 'Dietary exposure to BSE-contaminated neural tissue. Secondary human-to-human transmission via blood transfusion has occurred.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Oral ingestion.',
      spread: 'Transport across gut mucosa, replication in lymphoid tissue (tonsils, appendix), neural spread to brain.',
      organs: [ 'Brain', 'Lymphoid tissue' ],
      lesions: 'Spongiform encephalopathy.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'None.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'See BSE.',
        chronic: 'See BSE.',
        subclinical: 'See BSE.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Not applicable.',
        chronic: 'Prominent early psychiatric symptoms (depression, anxiety), sensory symptoms (sticky skin), ataxia, chorea, progressing to severe dementia and akinetic mutism. Death within 14 months of onset.',
        subclinical: 'Incubation period of 10-15+ years.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Cerebral atrophy.',
    histopathology: 'Florid plaques (amyloid core surrounded by a halo of spongiform vacuoles) in the cerebrum and cerebellum. Widespread PrP deposition in lymphoid tissues (unlike sporadic CJD).',
    sampleCollection: 'Tonsil biopsy (antemortem). Brain (postmortem).',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'Neuropathology and Western blot of brain tissue.',
    rapidTests: 'None.',
    serology: 'Not applicable.',
    pcr: 'Not applicable.',
    differentialDiagnosis: "Sporadic CJD (occurs in older patients, no florid plaques), Alzheimer's, Huntington's.",
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Palliative care. 100% fatal.',
    drugResistance: 'Not applicable.',
    vaccination: 'None.',
    biosecurity: 'Extreme care handling surgical instruments; prions resist standard autoclaving.',
    control: 'Strictly veterinary: controlling BSE in cattle through feed bans.',
    prevention: 'Removal of Specified Risk Materials (SRM) from the human food chain.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Caused immense global panic and permanently altered global food safety regulations.',
    onehealth: 'The ultimate lesson in food safety and the disastrous consequences of unnatural agricultural feeding practices.',
    economicImportance: 'Triggered multi-billion dollar trade disruptions.',
    indianContext: 'No cases reported, as BSE is absent in India.',
    globalContext: 'Vast majority of cases occurred in the UK. Incidence has dwindled to near zero.',
    recentAdvances: 'Blood screening tests under development to protect blood banks from asymptomatic carriers.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Human form of Mad Cow Disease. Psychiatric onset, florid plaques, fatal, controlled by fixing cattle feed.',
    quickRevision: 'Prion, vCJD, BSE, beef, psychiatric, florid plaques, tonsil biopsy, fatal.',
    references: [ 'WHO vCJD' ]
  },
  cryptococcosis: {
    definition: 'A systemic, opportunistic fungal disease caused by the Cryptococcus neoformans/gattii complex, characterized by respiratory, neurological, and cutaneous lesions.',
    historicalBackground: 'First isolated from peach juice in 1894 by Sanfelice. Recognized as a major opportunistic infection during the HIV/AIDS epidemic.',
    etiology: 'Cryptococcus neoformans (associated with pigeon guano, affects immunocompromised) and C. gattii (associated with Eucalyptus trees, affects immunocompetent).',
    taxonomy: 'Kingdom Fungi, Phylum Basidiomycota, Order Tremellales.',
    morphology: 'Dimorphic fungus, but exists purely as an encapsulated yeast in both the environment and host. Thick polysaccharide capsule is diagnostic.',
    hostRange: 'Cats (most susceptible domestic species), dogs, horses, birds, humans.',
    reservoir: 'Environment (soil, decaying wood). Birds are mechanical carriers (their high body temp prevents infection, but feces enrich the soil).',
    vectors: 'None.',
    carrierState: 'Not applicable. Environmental source.',
    envSurvival: 'Can survive for years in dry bird droppings protected from direct sunlight.',
    transmission: 'Inhalation of desiccated yeast cells or basidiospores from the environment.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Inhalation into the nasal cavity or lungs.',
      spread: 'Local infection in nasal cavity (cats) or lungs, followed by hematogenous dissemination, particularly neurotropism (crossing blood-brain barrier).',
      organs: [ 'Nasal cavity', 'Lungs', 'Brain/Meninges', 'Skin', 'Eyes' ],
      lesions: 'Gelatinous masses (due to thick capsule) replacing normal tissue with minimal inflammation.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Cell-mediated immunity is critical. The polysaccharide capsule heavily inhibits phagocytosis and suppresses local T-cell responses.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Rare.',
        chronic: "Cats: Sneezing, unilateral/bilateral mucopurulent or bloody nasal discharge, firm swelling over the bridge of the nose ('Roman nose'), cutaneous nodules, neurological signs (ataxia, seizures), chorioretinitis.",
        subclinical: 'Asymptomatic localized colonization may occur before immunosuppression triggers disease.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Rapid progression of meningoencephalitis in AIDS patients.',
        chronic: 'Headache, fever, neck stiffness, confusion, visual disturbances, pneumonia.',
        subclinical: 'Often self-limiting asymptomatic pulmonary infection in immunocompetent individuals.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: "Gelatinous, mucoid masses ('soap bubble' appearance) in the nasal cavity, brain, or lungs.",
    histopathology: 'Aggregates of encapsulated yeasts with a thick clear halo (capsule) visible on mucicarmine or India ink stain. Minimal granulomatous inflammation.',
    sampleCollection: 'Nasal swabs/exudate, fine needle aspirates of skin nodules, CSF, serum.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'Cytology of exudate/FNA mixed with India ink (highlights the capsule). Fungal culture on Sabouraud dextrose agar.',
    rapidTests: 'Latex agglutination test (LCAT) detecting cryptococcal capsular antigen in serum or CSF (highly sensitive and specific).',
    serology: 'LCAT antigen titer used for diagnosis and monitoring treatment response.',
    pcr: 'Available but LCAT antigen test is generally preferred due to speed, cost, and reliability.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Nasal tumors (lymphoma, adenocarcinoma), Aspergillosis, Sporotrichosis, FIP, Toxoplasmosis.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Prolonged therapy (months to years) using systemic antifungals (fluconazole, itraconazole, or amphotericin B).',
    drugResistance: 'Increasing reports of fluconazole resistance in C. neoformans.',
    vaccination: 'None available.',
    biosecurity: 'Standard hygiene. The disease is not transmitted directly from animals to humans.',
    control: 'Decontamination of areas with heavy pigeon droppings using 5% sodium hydroxide.',
    prevention: 'Preventing pet access to areas with high concentrations of bird droppings or decaying Eucalyptus matter.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Major cause of mortality in HIV/AIDS patients globally. Pets serve as environmental sentinels rather than direct sources of infection.',
    onehealth: 'Highlights the intersection of environmental ecology (trees, bird guano), host immunity, and shared exposure risks for pets and owners.',
    economicImportance: 'High cost of prolonged antifungal therapy in pets. Significant human healthcare burden.',
    indianContext: 'C. neoformans is highly prevalent in urban areas with large pigeon populations (e.g., temples, monuments).',
    globalContext: 'Global distribution. C. gattii emerged in the Pacific Northwest causing disease in immunocompetent animals and humans.',
    recentAdvances: 'Use of LFA (Lateral Flow Assay) for cryptococcal antigen has revolutionized point-of-care testing in both veterinary and human medicine.',
    keyTakeHome: "Environmental yeast with a massive capsule, causing 'Roman nose' in cats and fatal meningitis in humans; diagnosed via antigen LCAT.",
    quickRevision: 'Yeast, capsule, pigeon guano, Roman nose, cats, meningoencephalitis, India ink, LCAT antigen, fluconazole.',
    references: [ 'Merck Vet Manual', 'CDC Cryptococcosis' ]
  },
  aspergillosis: {
    definition: 'A spectrum of diseases caused by Aspergillus spp., ranging from localized infections (nasal/guttural pouch) to systemic/disseminated disease and mycotoxicosis.',
    historicalBackground: 'First described in birds in 1815. Recognized as a ubiquitous environmental mold affecting a wide array of species.',
    etiology: 'Aspergillus fumigatus (most common), A. flavus, A. niger, A. terreus. Ubiquitous environmental saprophytic molds.',
    taxonomy: 'Kingdom Fungi, Phylum Ascomycota, Family Trichocomaceae.',
    morphology: 'Septate hyphae with dichotomous, acute-angle (45 degree) branching. Conidiophores with terminal vesicles bearing chains of conidia.',
    hostRange: 'Birds (highly susceptible), dogs (nasal), horses (guttural pouch), cattle (mycotic abortion), humans.',
    reservoir: 'Environment (soil, decaying vegetation, moldy hay/feed).',
    vectors: 'None.',
    carrierState: 'Not applicable.',
    envSurvival: 'Spores are incredibly robust, surviving extreme environmental conditions and aerosolizing easily.',
    transmission: 'Inhalation of massive numbers of spores from moldy feed/bedding, or ingestion of pre-formed mycotoxins (aflatoxin).',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Inhalation into nasal cavity (dogs) or respiratory tract (birds), or ingestion of toxins.',
      spread: 'Spores evade mucociliary clearance, germinate into tissue-invasive hyphae. Produces proteases and toxins causing necrosis and vascular thrombosis.',
      organs: [
        'Nasal turbinates',
        'Lungs',
        'Air sacs (birds)',
        'Guttural pouch (horses)',
        'Placenta (cattle)'
      ],
      lesions: 'Necrotizing granulomatous inflammation, fungal plaques, cartilage/bone destruction.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Healthy immune systems (macrophages/neutrophils) clear spores rapidly. Disease usually requires overwhelming exposure or localized/systemic immune defects.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Brooder pneumonia in chicks: gasping, dyspnea, rapid death. Guttural pouch mycosis: sudden fatal epistaxis due to carotid artery erosion.',
        chronic: 'Canine nasal aspergillosis: chronic, profuse, purulent/hemorrhagic nasal discharge, facial pain, ulceration of nares. Mycotic abortion in cattle (late term).',
        subclinical: 'Animals often carry spores without disease.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Invasive pulmonary aspergillosis in neutropenic patients (high mortality).',
        chronic: "Aspergilloma ('fungus ball' in old TB cavities), Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis (ABPA).",
        subclinical: 'Daily inhalation of spores by all humans with no clinical effect.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Yellow/green/black fuzzy fungal plaques (mycetomas) on mucosa. Severe destruction of nasal turbinates (dogs). Thickened, cloudy air sacs (birds).',
    histopathology: 'Necrosis, thrombosis, and intense granulomatous inflammation with branching, septate hyphae invading tissues (PAS or Silver stain).',
    sampleCollection: 'Nasal biopsies/plaques via rhinoscopy (dogs), tracheal wash, placenta/fetal stomach contents.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: "Cytology/histopathology showing tissue invasion (crucial). Fungal culture on Sabouraud dextrose agar (must correlate with clinical signs, as it's a common environmental contaminant).",
    rapidTests: 'Detection of Galactomannan antigen in serum or BAL fluid.',
    serology: 'Agar gel immunodiffusion (AGID) or ELISA for Aspergillus antibodies (useful in canine nasal disease).',
    pcr: 'Available but prone to false positives due to environmental contamination.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Nasal tumors, foreign bodies, Pasteurellosis, Mycoplasmosis (poultry).',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Topical infusion of antifungals (clotrimazole/enilconazole) for canine nasal disease. Systemic therapy (itraconazole, voriconazole) for disseminated disease. Surgical occlusion of carotid artery for horses.',
    drugResistance: 'Emerging resistance to azoles in A. fumigatus due to agricultural fungicide use.',
    vaccination: 'None available.',
    biosecurity: 'Avoid moldy bedding and feed. Ensure proper ventilation in poultry houses.',
    control: 'Strict environmental management. Removing contaminated hay/litter.',
    prevention: 'Proper storage of grains and feed to prevent mold growth and aflatoxin production.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Major opportunistic pathogen in immunocompromised humans. Zoonotic transmission does not occur directly from animals; both share the environmental source.',
    onehealth: 'Agricultural use of azole fungicides driving drug resistance in human/veterinary Aspergillus isolates is a critical One Health issue.',
    economicImportance: 'Major cause of economic loss in the poultry industry and dairy industry (abortions).',
    indianContext: 'High humidity and poor feed storage conditions lead to high incidence of both infectious Aspergillosis and Aflatoxicosis in livestock.',
    globalContext: 'Ubiquitous global pathogen.',
    recentAdvances: 'Development of non-invasive CT-guided topical infusion techniques for canine nasal aspergillosis.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Environmental mold causing severe localized (nasal/guttural pouch) or respiratory (birds) necrotizing disease. Requires tissue biopsy for definitive diagnosis.',
    quickRevision: 'Mold, 45-degree branching, nasal discharge, guttural pouch epistaxis, brooder pneumonia, clotrimazole infusion.',
    references: [ 'Merck Vet Manual', 'WOAH Terrestrial Manual' ]
  },
  sporotrichosis: {
    definition: "Sporotrichosis ('Rose Gardener’s Disease') is a chronic, cutaneous, and lymphocutaneous granulomatous fungal infection caused by Sporothrix species.",
    historicalBackground: 'First described by Schenck in 1898. Recognized as an occupational hazard for gardeners and agricultural workers.',
    etiology: 'Sporothrix schenckii complex, and notably Sporothrix brasiliensis (highly virulent, feline-associated clade).',
    taxonomy: 'Kingdom Fungi, Phylum Ascomycota, Order Ophiostomatales.',
    morphology: "Dimorphic fungus. Mycelial form in the environment (slender hyphae with 'daisy-head' conidia). Pleomorphic, cigar-shaped yeast form in tissues.",
    hostRange: 'Humans, cats (highly susceptible), dogs, horses.',
    reservoir: 'Environment (soil, sphagnum moss, rose bushes, decaying wood). Cats serve as a major reservoir for S. brasiliensis.',
    vectors: 'Mechanical transmission via thorns, splinters, or animal scratches/bites.',
    carrierState: 'Subclinical carriage can occur in cats.',
    envSurvival: 'Survives indefinitely in organic-rich soil and plant material.',
    transmission: 'Traumatic inoculation of environmental material. For S. brasiliensis, directly transmitted via scratches/bites from infected cats.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Subcutaneous inoculation via trauma.',
      spread: 'Local multiplication, conversion to yeast phase. Spreads proximally along the lymphatic vessels.',
      organs: [ 'Skin', 'Subcutis', 'Lymphatics' ],
      lesions: 'Nodular, granulomatous, and ulcerative skin lesions that follow the course of lymphatic drainage.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Granulomatous response (macrophages, giant cells) attempts to wall off the yeast. Cell-mediated immunity is key.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Cats: Severe, non-healing, ulcerated cutaneous nodules, often on the head, base of the tail, or limbs. Sneezing if nasal mucosa is involved.',
        chronic: 'Horses: Firm subcutaneous nodules along the lymphatics of the distal limbs, which may ulcerate and discharge pus.',
        subclinical: 'Dogs often exhibit less severe, localized cutaneous disease.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Primary painless papule at the site of inoculation (e.g., finger), which ulcerates.',
        chronic: 'Development of secondary nodules ascending along the regional lymphatic vessels (lymphocutaneous form).',
        subclinical: 'Rare.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Ulcerated, draining subcutaneous nodules along lymphatic tracts.',
    histopathology: 'Pyogranulomatous inflammation. Yeast cells are often sparse in dogs/horses but extremely numerous in cats. Asteroid bodies (yeast surrounded by radiating eosinophilic material) may be seen.',
    sampleCollection: 'Exudate from ulcers, fine needle aspirates of intact nodules, tissue biopsies.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'Cytology of feline lesions easily reveals abundant cigar-shaped yeasts. Fungal culture is definitive (demonstrating dimorphism at 25C and 37C).',
    rapidTests: 'None.',
    serology: 'Rarely used in veterinary medicine.',
    pcr: 'Available in specialized labs for speciation (differentiating S. schenckii from S. brasiliensis).',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Epizootic lymphangitis (Histoplasma farciminosum in horses), Glanders, Cutaneous Leishmaniasis, Cryptococcosis, Mycobacterial infections.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Systemic itraconazole is the treatment of choice for cats and dogs. Potassium iodide (supersaturated) is a traditional, cheap option for horses/cattle.',
    drugResistance: 'Some resistance noted in S. brasiliensis to standard antifungals.',
    vaccination: 'None available.',
    biosecurity: 'Veterinarians and owners must wear gloves when handling cats with ulcerated skin lesions.',
    control: 'Strict isolation of infected cats during treatment.',
    prevention: 'Wearing gloves when gardening. Prompt cleaning of cat scratches.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Major zoonosis. S. brasiliensis has caused a massive, ongoing zoonotic epidemic in South America, transmitted directly from cats to humans.',
    onehealth: 'The shift of Sporothrix from an environmental pathogen (S. schenckii) to a highly virulent, animal-to-human transmitted pathogen (S. brasiliensis) represents a significant evolutionary One Health event.',
    economicImportance: 'Veterinary costs for prolonged treatment. Occupational hazard resulting in lost work days for humans.',
    indianContext: 'Reported sporadically in humans (agricultural areas) and animals, though not at epidemic levels seen in South America.',
    globalContext: 'Endemic worldwide, but S. brasiliensis is hyperendemic in Brazil and spreading across South America.',
    recentAdvances: 'Molecular epidemiology mapping the rapid geographic expansion of the cat-associated S. brasiliensis epidemic.',
    keyTakeHome: "Dimorphic fungus causing 'cigar-shaped' yeasts in lymphocutaneous ulcers. Cats are highly infectious sources of zoonotic transmission.",
    quickRevision: 'Dimorphic, cigar-shaped yeast, rose-gardener, lymphocutaneous, cats highly infectious, itraconazole, S. brasiliensis.',
    references: [ 'Merck Vet Manual', 'CDC Sporotrichosis' ]
  },
  scrapie: {
    definition: 'Scrapie is a fatal, degenerative disease affecting the central nervous system of sheep and goats, and is the prototype transmissible spongiform encephalopathy (TSE).',
    historicalBackground: 'Recognized in European sheep for over 250 years. Name derives from the intense pruritus causing animals to scrape their fleeces off.',
    etiology: 'Prion (PrP^Sc), an abnormal isoform of the cellular prion protein (PrP^C).',
    taxonomy: 'Not applicable.',
    morphology: 'Forms amyloid fibrils and aggregates in neural and lymphoid tissues.',
    hostRange: 'Sheep, goats, and mouflon.',
    reservoir: 'Infected sheep and goats; heavily contaminated pastures/environments.',
    vectors: 'None.',
    carrierState: 'Prolonged incubation period (1-5 years) where animals shed the agent in placenta and fluids.',
    envSurvival: 'Extremely resilient. Can persist in pastures and sheepfolds for years, remaining infectious.',
    transmission: 'Direct contact, ingestion of infected placenta/allantoic fluids during lambing, and environmental contamination.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Oral ingestion.',
      spread: "Replication in tonsils and gut-associated lymphoid tissue (GALT), particularly Peyer's patches. Ascension via autonomic nerves to the CNS.",
      organs: [ 'Lymph nodes', 'Spleen', 'Brain', 'Spinal cord', 'Placenta' ],
      lesions: 'Spongiform encephalopathy without inflammation.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'No immune response elicited.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Rarely seen.',
        chronic: 'Intense pruritus (rubbing, scraping), wool loss, lip smacking (nibble reflex), ataxia, high-stepping gait, tremors, wasting, death.',
        subclinical: 'Asymptomatic carriers shed prions during lambing.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Not applicable.',
        chronic: 'Not known to cause disease in humans (unlike BSE).',
        subclinical: 'Not applicable.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Non-specific. Wool loss and skin excoriations secondary to rubbing.',
    histopathology: 'Spongiform vacuolation of neurons in the brainstem and spinal cord. Prominent astrogliosis.',
    sampleCollection: 'Brainstem (obex), retropharyngeal lymph nodes, tonsil. Live animal testing via rectal mucosal biopsy or third eyelid lymphoid tissue.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'Detection of PrP^Sc via immunohistochemistry (IHC) or Western blot.',
    rapidTests: 'ELISA on brain or lymphoid tissue.',
    serology: 'Not applicable.',
    pcr: 'Not applicable.',
    differentialDiagnosis: "Ectoparasites (lice, scabies), Aujeszky's disease, Maedi-Visna, Rabies, Pregnancy toxemia.",
    treatmentPrinciples: 'No treatment. Fatal.',
    drugResistance: 'Not applicable.',
    vaccination: 'No vaccine available.',
    biosecurity: 'Thorough cleaning of lambing areas. Chemical disinfection requires 1N NaOH or strong sodium hypochlorite.',
    control: 'Genotyping and selective breeding for resistance (e.g., ARR/ARR genotype in sheep). Culling of susceptible/infected animals.',
    prevention: 'Maintaining closed flocks, purchasing sheep with resistant genotypes.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Zero known risk to humans. Scrapie does not cause human TSEs, but remains heavily regulated to distinguish from BSE.',
    onehealth: 'Highlights the importance of species barriers in prion diseases, contrasting sharply with the zoonotic nature of BSE.',
    economicImportance: 'Significant losses due to culling, export restrictions, and reduced production efficiency.',
    indianContext: 'Rare/unreported in indigenous breeds, but strict surveillance exists for imported exotic breeds.',
    globalContext: 'Endemic in many parts of the world, though some countries (e.g., Australia, New Zealand) are officially free.',
    recentAdvances: 'Extensive use of genetic selection programs has drastically reduced scrapie prevalence in Europe.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Contagious prion disease of sheep/goats, presents with intense pruritus and ataxia, managed through genetic breeding for resistance.',
    quickRevision: 'Prion, sheep/goats, scraping, nibble reflex, third eyelid biopsy, ARR genotype, non-zoonotic.',
    references: [
      'WOAH Terrestrial Manual',
      'Merck Vet Manual',
      'DEFRA guidelines'
    ]
  },
  cwd: {
    definition: 'Chronic Wasting Disease (CWD) is a highly contagious, fatal transmissible spongiform encephalopathy (TSE) of cervids (deer, elk, reindeer, moose).',
    historicalBackground: 'First identified in captive mule deer in Colorado in 1967. Has since spread widely across North America and recently detected in Scandinavia.',
    etiology: "Prion (PrP^CWD), misfolded conformer of the host's normal prion protein.",
    taxonomy: 'Not applicable.',
    morphology: 'Amyloid plaques and fibrils in CNS and lymphoid tissues.',
    hostRange: 'Cervids (mule deer, white-tailed deer, elk, moose, caribou).',
    reservoir: 'Infected cervids and heavily contaminated environments.',
    vectors: 'None.',
    carrierState: 'Long incubation (16-36 months) with continuous shedding of prions in saliva, urine, and feces before onset of clinical signs.',
    envSurvival: 'Binds to soil particles (especially clay) and remains highly infectious in the environment for years/decades.',
    transmission: 'Direct animal-to-animal contact, and indirect transmission via environmentally contaminated soil, water, and forage.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Oral or intranasal exposure.',
      spread: 'Rapid dissemination to lymphoid tissues (tonsils, retropharyngeal lymph nodes) before spreading to the CNS via peripheral nerves.',
      organs: [ 'Tonsils', 'Lymph nodes', 'Brain', 'Spinal cord' ],
      lesions: 'Progressive spongiform degeneration of the brain.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'No inflammatory or immune response.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Not applicable.',
        chronic: 'Severe progressive weight loss (wasting), behavioral changes (loss of fear of humans), excessive salivation, polyuria/polydipsia, drooping ears, death.',
        subclinical: 'Animals appear completely normal but actively shed infectious prions.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'No known cases.',
        chronic: 'No known human cases to date, though public health agencies strongly advise against consuming meat from CWD-positive animals.',
        subclinical: 'Not applicable.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Emaciation, aspiration pneumonia (frequent terminal event), megaesophagus.',
    histopathology: 'Spongiform changes and prominent florid amyloid plaques in the brainstem, thalamus, and olfactory bulb.',
    sampleCollection: 'Medial retropharyngeal lymph nodes (RLN) and obex. Live animal testing via tonsil or rectal biopsy.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'Immunohistochemistry (IHC) (gold standard) or ELISA on RLN or obex.',
    rapidTests: 'ELISA used for high-throughput screening of hunter-harvested deer.',
    serology: 'Not applicable.',
    pcr: 'Not applicable.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Starvation, Dental attrition, Brain abscesses, Epizootic Hemorrhagic Disease (EHD), Parasitism.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'No treatment. Uniformly fatal.',
    drugResistance: 'Not applicable.',
    vaccination: 'No vaccine available.',
    biosecurity: 'Proper carcass disposal via alkaline hydrolysis, incineration, or deep burial in approved landfills. Avoid moving carcasses across jurisdictions.',
    control: 'Depopulation of infected captive herds. Enhanced surveillance and hunting restrictions in wild populations.',
    prevention: 'Banning baiting/feeding of wild deer to prevent congregation. Restricting carcass movement.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Zoonotic potential remains uncertain. Precautionary principle dictates testing and avoidance of infected meat.',
    onehealth: 'Represents a profound wildlife management and environmental health crisis due to unstoppable environmental contamination and potential species barrier crossing.',
    economicImportance: 'Devastating impacts on the hunting industry, wildlife conservation funding, and captive cervid farming.',
    indianContext: 'Not reported in India. Relevant only if importing exotic cervids.',
    globalContext: 'Endemic in North America. Recently emerged in Norway, posing a new threat to European reindeer and moose populations.',
    recentAdvances: 'Use of RT-QuIC for detecting prions in environmental samples (soil, water) and non-invasive samples (feces).',
    keyTakeHome: 'Highly contagious prion disease of deer/elk, causing fatal wasting, with massive environmental persistence and uncertain zoonotic risk.',
    quickRevision: 'Prion, cervids, wasting, polyuria, environmental contamination, RLN, RT-QuIC, hunting restrictions.',
    references: [
      'WOAH Terrestrial Manual',
      'CDC CWD Guidelines',
      'USGS Wildlife Health'
    ]
  },
  echinococcosis: {
    definition: 'A severe, chronic zoonotic helminthic disease caused by the larval stages (metacestodes) of Echinococcus tapeworms, primarily resulting in cystic (CE) or alveolar (AE) echinococcosis in intermediate hosts, including humans.',
    historicalBackground: "Hydatid cysts recognized by Hippocrates as 'livers full of water'. Life cycle elucidated by von Siebold in 1853.",
    etiology: 'Echinococcus granulosus sensu lato (causes Cystic Echinococcosis - CE) and E. multilocularis (causes Alveolar Echinococcosis - AE).',
    taxonomy: 'Phylum Platyhelminthes, Class Cestoda, Order Cyclophyllidea, Family Taeniidae.',
    morphology: "Adult tapeworm (in definitive host gut) is tiny (2-7 mm) with 3-4 proglottids. Larval stage (in intermediate host) forms fluid-filled hydatid cysts containing thousands of protoscoleces ('hydatid sand').",
    hostRange: 'Definitive hosts: Dogs, wolves, foxes (canids). Intermediate hosts: Sheep, cattle, pigs, camels (CE); rodents (AE); Humans (accidental intermediate).',
    reservoir: 'Sylvatic cycle (wolves/moose, foxes/voles) and Pastoral/Domestic cycle (dogs/sheep).',
    vectors: 'None. Direct environmental contamination.',
    carrierState: 'Dogs harbor adult worms for months without signs, shedding eggs.',
    envSurvival: 'Taeniid eggs survive freezing and persist in the environment for months, but are sensitive to desiccation and heat (>60°C).',
    transmission: 'Fecal-oral. Intermediate hosts/humans ingest eggs from contaminated pasture, water, soil, or dog fur. Dogs get infected by eating offal containing hydatid cysts.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Ingestion of eggs.',
      spread: 'Oncosphere hatches in intestine, penetrates mucosa, travels via portal vein. Trapped in liver (capillary bed 1) or lungs (capillary bed 2).',
      organs: [ 'Liver (70%)', 'Lungs (20%)', 'Brain/Bone (rare)' ],
      lesions: 'E. granulosus: Unilocular expanding fluid cyst. E. multilocularis: Infiltrative, tumor-like multilocular cyst destroying liver parenchyma.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'The thick laminated layer of the cyst evades host immunity. Leakage of cyst fluid can trigger massive IgE-mediated anaphylaxis.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Dogs: Asymptomatic.',
        chronic: 'Livestock: Usually asymptomatic, incidental finding at abattoir. Heavy infections cause reduced yield.',
        subclinical: 'Standard state for most animals.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Anaphylactic shock if a cyst ruptures (e.g., trauma or surgery).',
        chronic: 'CE: Abdominal pain, hepatomegaly, jaundice (biliary compression), chronic cough (lung cysts). AE: Severe liver failure, mimics hepatic carcinoma.',
        subclinical: 'Can be asymptomatic for decades as cysts grow 1-5 cm/year.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Liver/Lungs: Large fluid-filled cysts with a thick, opaque white wall (CE). Spongy, invasive, calcified masses in liver (AE).',
    histopathology: 'Cyst wall consists of an outer acellular laminated layer and an inner germinal layer producing brood capsules with hooklet-bearing protoscoleces. Host encapsulates with fibrous tissue.',
    sampleCollection: 'Serum (humans). Feces (dogs). Cysts at necropsy/slaughter.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: "Imaging (Ultrasound pathognomonic 'water lily' sign). Serology. Microscopic detection of hooklets in aspirate.",
    rapidTests: 'Coproantigen ELISA for testing dog feces.',
    serology: 'ELISA, Indirect Hemagglutination (IHA), confirmed by Western Blot (detecting specific bands like Em18 for AE).',
    pcr: 'PCR on dog feces or cyst tissue for species/strain typing (G1-G10).',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Hepatic cysts (simple), Abscesses, Hepatic carcinoma, Taenia hydatigena (Cysticercus tenuicollis in sheep).',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Humans (CE): PAIR (Puncture, Aspiration, Injection of scolicidal, Re-aspiration), surgery, and prolonged Albendazole. Dogs: Praziquantel.',
    drugResistance: 'None reported, but albendazole is only virostatic in AE, requiring lifelong therapy.',
    vaccination: 'EG95 vaccine available for sheep, highly effective at preventing hydatid cyst establishment, breaking the domestic cycle.',
    biosecurity: 'Never feed raw offal to dogs. Strict abattoir meat inspection and condemnation of infected organs.',
    control: 'Regular 6-weekly deworming of dogs with Praziquantel in endemic areas. Stray dog control.',
    prevention: 'Hand hygiene, washing vegetables, controlling access of dogs to slaughterhouses.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Major neglected tropical disease (NTD). AE is one of the most lethal helminthic infections in humans (high mortality without treatment).',
    onehealth: 'Control absolutely requires a One Health approach: vaccinating sheep, deworming dogs, improving abattoir hygiene, and public education.',
    economicImportance: 'Significant economic loss from condemned offal (livers/lungs) and severe human healthcare costs.',
    indianContext: 'E. granulosus (G1 sheep strain, G5 cattle strain) is highly endemic due to the widespread practice of backyard slaughter and presence of stray dogs.',
    globalContext: 'E. granulosus is worldwide (sheep-raising areas). E. multilocularis restricted to Northern Hemisphere (Europe, Asia, North America).',
    recentAdvances: 'Development and application of the recombinant EG95 sheep vaccine in control programs (e.g., in Argentina and China).',
    keyTakeHome: 'Dog-sheep cycle. Humans get infected by ingesting dog feces, developing massive liver/lung cysts. Prevent by not feeding raw offal to dogs.',
    quickRevision: 'Hydatid cyst, E. granulosus, dog-sheep cycle, liver, anaphylaxis, PAIR, hooklets, Praziquantel for dogs.',
    references: [ 'WHO Echinococcosis', 'OIE Terrestrial Manual' ]
  },
  leishmaniasis: {
    definition: 'Leishmaniasis is a vector-borne protozoan disease causing Visceral (Kala-azar), Cutaneous, or Mucocutaneous forms in humans and dogs.',
    historicalBackground: 'Identified by Leishman and Donovan in 1903 in patients in India. Sandfly transmission proven in the 1940s.',
    etiology: 'Leishmania infantum (syn. L. chagasi), L. donovani (Visceral), L. tropica, L. major (Cutaneous).',
    taxonomy: 'Phylum Euglenozoa, Class Kinetoplastea, Order Trypanosomatida, Family Trypanosomatidae.',
    morphology: 'Promastigote (motile, flagellated) in the sandfly midgut. Amastigote (non-motile, oval, containing a nucleus and rod-like kinetoplast) inside host macrophages.',
    hostRange: 'Humans, Dogs (primary reservoir for L. infantum), wild canids, rodents.',
    reservoir: 'Dogs (Canine Leishmaniasis - CanL) for L. infantum. Humans (Anthroponotic) for L. donovani in India. Rodents for L. major.',
    vectors: 'Female phlebotomine sandflies (Phlebotomus in Old World, Lutzomyia in New World).',
    carrierState: 'Many dogs in endemic areas are infected subclinically but remain infectious to sandflies.',
    envSurvival: 'Obligate parasite, does not survive in the environment.',
    transmission: 'Bite of an infected sandfly. Vertical (transplacental), venereal, and blood transfusion transmission also occur in dogs.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Sandfly injects promastigotes into skin.',
      spread: 'Phagocytosed by macrophages, transform to amastigotes, multiply and burst cell, infecting other macrophages. Disseminate to RES (spleen, liver, bone marrow).',
      organs: [
        'Skin',
        'Spleen',
        'Liver',
        'Bone marrow',
        'Lymph nodes',
        'Kidneys (immune complex damage)'
      ],
      lesions: 'Granulomatous inflammation, marked lymphoid hyperplasia followed by depletion, immune-complex glomerulonephritis.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Crucial dichotomy: Th1 (cellular) response controls infection (asymptomatic). Th2 (humoral) response leads to uncontrolled parasite multiplication, hypergammaglobulinemia, and fatal disease.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Rare in dogs.',
        chronic: "CanL: Exfoliative dermatitis, alopecia (especially periorbital 'spectacles'), onychogryphosis (long overgrown nails), epistaxis, weight loss, lymphadenopathy, renal failure.",
        subclinical: 'High proportion of infected dogs in endemic areas.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Spiking fever, pancytopenia.',
        chronic: "Visceral: Hepatosplenomegaly, cachexia, hyperpigmentation ('Kala-azar' = black fever), fatal if untreated. Cutaneous: Chronic painless ulcer ('Oriental sore').",
        subclinical: 'Common in L. infantum endemic areas.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Splenomegaly, hepatomegaly, generalized lymphadenopathy. Pale kidneys (nephritis).',
    histopathology: 'Macrophages packed with Leishman-Donovan (LD) bodies (amastigotes). Membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis due to immune complex deposition.',
    sampleCollection: 'Bone marrow aspirate, lymph node aspirate, splenic aspirate, skin scrape.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'Cytology (Giemsa stain showing intracellular amastigotes with distinct kinetoplast). IFAT or ELISA for antibodies.',
    rapidTests: 'rK39 dipstick test is highly specific and sensitive for visceral leishmaniasis (dogs and humans).',
    serology: 'Quantitative IFAT is the gold standard for clinical staging in dogs.',
    pcr: 'Real-time PCR on bone marrow or conjunctival swabs (highly sensitive for detecting asymptomatic carrier dogs).',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Ehrlichiosis, Babesiosis, Lymphoma, Demodicosis, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Dogs: Meglumine antimoniate + Allopurinol (lifelong to prevent relapse) or Miltefosine. Cures are rare; aims for clinical remission. Humans: Liposomal Amphotericin B.',
    drugResistance: 'Antimony resistance is widespread in L. donovani (India).',
    vaccination: "Canine vaccines available (e.g., LetiFend, CaniLeish) utilizing recombinant proteins, but only reduce risk of clinical progression, don't prevent infection.",
    biosecurity: 'Not directly contagious (except blood/vertical). Focus on vector control.',
    control: 'Topical pyrethroid insecticides (collars/spot-ons) for dogs to repel sandflies. Culling of seropositive dogs (controversial and often ineffective).',
    prevention: 'Keeping dogs indoors at dawn/dusk when sandflies feed. Use of fine-mesh screens.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Visceral leishmaniasis is fatal without treatment. Zoonotic L. infantum relies entirely on the canine reservoir.',
    onehealth: 'Controlling human infantile visceral leishmaniasis in the Mediterranean/South America relies entirely on controlling canine leishmaniasis and managing the sandfly vector.',
    economicImportance: 'Significant veterinary costs for lifelong management in dogs. Major public health burden in endemic countries.',
    indianContext: 'L. donovani (Kala-azar) is anthroponotic (human-to-human via sandfly) in Bihar/UP. Zoonotic L. infantum is occasionally reported in dogs in Kerala/Himalayas.',
    globalContext: 'Endemic in the Mediterranean basin, Middle East, Brazil, and parts of Asia.',
    recentAdvances: 'Widespread use of Liposomal Amphotericin B in human medicine, and the roll-out of the rK39 rapid test, severely cutting mortality rates.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Vector-borne (sandfly) protozoan. Causes severe exfoliative dermatitis and renal failure in dogs. Dogs are the reservoir for human visceral disease.',
    quickRevision: 'Amastigote, sandfly, Kala-azar, L. infantum, canine reservoir, overgrown nails, spectacles, rK39, allopurinol.',
    references: [ 'WHO Leishmaniasis', 'LeishVet Guidelines' ]
  },
  cysticercosis: {
    definition: 'A tissue infection caused by the larval cysticercus stage of Taenia tapeworms. Most critically, Taenia solium cysticercosis causes severe neurological disease (Neurocysticercosis) in humans.',
    historicalBackground: 'Known since ancient times. The link between the adult tapeworm in humans and cysts in pigs was established by Küchenmeister in the 1850s.',
    etiology: 'Taenia solium (Pork tapeworm) and Taenia saginata (Beef tapeworm).',
    taxonomy: 'Phylum Platyhelminthes, Class Cestoda, Order Cyclophyllidea, Family Taeniidae.',
    morphology: 'Adults in human intestine (scolex with 4 suckers; T. solium has a rostellum with hooks, T. saginata does not). Cysticercus (larva) is a fluid-filled bladder (~1 cm) containing a single invaginated scolex.',
    hostRange: 'T. solium: Pigs (intermediate), Humans (definitive AND accidental intermediate). T. saginata: Cattle (intermediate), Humans (definitive only).',
    reservoir: 'Humans harboring the adult tapeworm (taeniasis) shed eggs, contaminating the environment.',
    vectors: 'Mechanical vectors like dung beetles/flies can spread eggs.',
    carrierState: 'Pigs harbor cysticerci in muscles asymptomatically until slaughter. Humans harbor adult tapeworms for years.',
    envSurvival: 'Taeniid eggs can survive in pastures, water, and soil for months.',
    transmission: "Pigs/Cattle ingest eggs from human feces. Humans get TAENIASIS by eating undercooked 'measly' pork/beef. Humans get CYSTICERCOSIS (T. solium only) by ingesting eggs (fecal-oral).",
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Ingestion of eggs (causing cysticercosis) or cysticerci (causing taeniasis).',
      spread: 'Eggs hatch into oncospheres, penetrate gut, travel via blood to striated muscle, heart, and brain, encysting as Cysticercus cellulosae (pork) or bovis (beef).',
      organs: [
        'Skeletal muscle',
        'Heart',
        'Brain (T. solium in humans)',
        'Eye'
      ],
      lesions: 'Cysts provoke minimal reaction while alive, but massive granulomatous inflammation and edema upon death.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Live cysts evade immunity via immunosuppressive molecules. Dying cysts expose antigens, triggering intense inflammation (causing seizures in neurocysticercosis).',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Usually none.',
        chronic: 'Pigs and Cattle are generally asymptomatic. Heavy infections may cause muscle stiffness.',
        subclinical: 'Standard presentation; cysts found incidentally at meat inspection.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Taeniasis: Mild abdominal discomfort, passing proglottids.',
        chronic: 'Neurocysticercosis (NCC): Adult-onset seizures, chronic headaches, intracranial hypertension, psychiatric disturbances, hydrocephalus.',
        subclinical: 'Subcutaneous/muscular cysticercosis is often painless and unnoticed.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Translucent, oval vesicles (5-10 mm) containing a white spot (the scolex) in the myocardium, masseter, tongue, and diaphragm.',
    histopathology: 'Bladder wall with microtriches, calcareous corpuscles, and an invaginated scolex. Degenerating cysts show caseous necrosis and calcification.',
    sampleCollection: 'Meat inspection (masseter, heart, diaphragm). Human serum/CSF.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: "Meat inspection (incisions into predilection sites). In humans: CT/MRI of brain showing cysts with 'dot' (scolex).",
    rapidTests: 'None routine for animals.',
    serology: 'Enzyme-linked Immunoelectrotransfer Blot (EITB) is highly specific for detecting human antibodies.',
    pcr: 'Rarely used clinically.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Pigs: Trichinellosis, Toxoplasmosis, Sarcocystosis. Humans (NCC): Brain tumor, Tuberculosis, Echinococcosis.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Animals: None (condemnation at slaughter). Humans (NCC): Albendazole or Praziquantel WITH high-dose corticosteroids to control inflammation from dying cysts. Surgery for hydrocephalus.',
    drugResistance: 'Not significant.',
    vaccination: 'TSOL18 vaccine for pigs is highly effective, blocking the lifecycle when combined with oxfendazole treatment.',
    biosecurity: 'Proper sanitation. Stopping open human defecation near pig scavenging areas.',
    control: 'Strict meat inspection (condemnation of heavy infections, freezing -10°C for 14 days for light infections).',
    prevention: 'Cooking pork/beef thoroughly. Handwashing. Treating human tapeworm carriers (Praziquantel).',
    publicHealthImportance: 'T. solium neurocysticercosis is the leading cause of preventable epilepsy globally, causing 30% of epilepsy cases in endemic areas.',
    onehealth: 'Eradication requires halting open defecation, managing free-roaming pigs, and implementing the TSOL18 pig vaccine—a classic One Health triad.',
    economicImportance: 'Significant losses due to meat condemnation and massive human healthcare costs for epilepsy management.',
    indianContext: 'Highly endemic in regions where free-ranging pigs have access to human feces. Major cause of epilepsy in North India.',
    globalContext: 'Endemic in Latin America, Sub-Saharan Africa, and Southeast Asia. Eradicated in Western Europe.',
    recentAdvances: 'Validation of the TSOL18 vaccine and mass drug administration (MDA) of pigs/humans towards regional elimination goals.',
    keyTakeHome: 'T. solium eggs cause brain cysts (seizures) in humans. Humans get the tapeworm from undercooked pork. Prevent by cooking pork and stopping open defecation.',
    quickRevision: 'T. solium, neurocysticercosis, pigs, epilepsy, measly pork, open defecation, masseter muscle, TSOL18 vaccine.',
    references: [ 'WHO Taeniasis/Cysticercosis', 'OIE Terrestrial Manual' ]
  },
  schistosomiasis: {
    definition: "A water-borne, acute and chronic disease caused by blood flukes of the genus Schistosoma. Also causes 'Swimmer's Itch' (cercarial dermatitis) via avian schistosomes.",
    historicalBackground: 'Eggs discovered in Egyptian mummies. Life cycle involving snails elucidated in the early 20th century.',
    etiology: "Schistosoma japonicum, S. mekongi (major zoonotic species). S. mansoni and S. haematobium (mostly human-to-human). Trichobilharzia (avian, causes swimmer's itch).",
    taxonomy: 'Phylum Platyhelminthes, Class Trematoda, Subclass Digenea, Family Schistosomatidae.',
    morphology: 'Adults are dioecious (separate sexes); the male has a gynecophoric canal in which the female resides. Eggs lack an operculum and have a characteristic spine (lateral or terminal) or are round (S. japonicum).',
    hostRange: 'S. japonicum: Humans, cattle, water buffalo, pigs, dogs. Avian schistosomes: Waterfowl.',
    reservoir: 'Water buffalo and cattle are the primary maintenance hosts for S. japonicum in Asia.',
    vectors: 'Intermediate hosts: Freshwater snails (Oncomelania for S. japonicum, Biomphalaria for S. mansoni).',
    carrierState: 'Adult worms live for 3-10 years in the mesenteric veins, continuously producing eggs.',
    envSurvival: 'Miracidia and cercariae survive only for hours in freshwater and must find a snail or mammalian host rapidly.',
    transmission: 'Skin penetration by free-swimming cercariae in contaminated freshwater.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Cercariae penetrate intact skin, shed tails, become schistosomula.',
      spread: 'Migrate via blood to lungs, then liver to mature. Adults migrate to mesenteric veins (S. japonicum/mansoni) or venous plexus of bladder (S. haematobium).',
      organs: [ 'Skin', 'Liver', 'Intestines', 'Bladder' ],
      lesions: "Pathology is driven by the eggs, not adult worms. Eggs trapped in tissues induce intense granulomatous inflammation and progressive fibrosis (Symmers' pipe-stem fibrosis in liver)."
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Th2-mediated granuloma formation around eggs. Adult worms evade immunity by coating themselves in host blood antigens.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Often asymptomatic.',
        chronic: 'Cattle/Buffalo: Diarrhea, weight loss, lethargy, reduced milk yield. Heavy infections lead to ascites and emaciation.',
        subclinical: 'Most livestock act as silent reservoirs.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Katayama fever (systemic hypersensitivity): fever, urticaria, eosinophilia, cough.',
        chronic: 'Hepatosplenomegaly, portal hypertension, ascites, esophageal varices. S. haematobium causes hematuria and bladder cancer.',
        subclinical: "Cercarial dermatitis (Swimmer's itch): intense pruritic maculopapular rash from non-human schistosomes dying in the skin."
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Liver: Severe fibrosis (clay-pipe stem). Intestines: Edematous, thickened mucosa with polyps and petechiae.',
    histopathology: 'Granulomas surrounding schistosome eggs (often calcified) in the hepatic portal tracts and intestinal submucosa.',
    sampleCollection: 'Feces (S. japonicum, S. mansoni), Urine (S. haematobium). Tissue biopsy (rectal).',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'Microscopic detection of eggs in stool/urine. Kato-Katz thick smear technique.',
    rapidTests: 'Point-of-care circulating cathodic antigen (CCA) urine test.',
    serology: 'ELISA for antibodies, but cannot distinguish past from present infection.',
    pcr: 'Real-time PCR on stool/blood is highly sensitive but expensive.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Fascioliasis, Hepatic cirrhosis (viral), Malaria, Leishmaniasis.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Praziquantel is highly effective against adult worms (but not immature schistosomula).',
    drugResistance: 'Rare, but reduced efficacy of Praziquantel has been reported, prompting vigilance.',
    vaccination: 'None available for humans. Bovine vaccines (SjCTPI) are under development to reduce egg shedding in water buffalo.',
    biosecurity: 'Safe water supply, proper sanitation.',
    control: 'Mass drug administration (MDA) of Praziquantel in endemic areas. Molluscicides to kill snails (environmental toxicity concerns).',
    prevention: 'Avoid swimming/wading in freshwater in endemic areas. Treat livestock (buffalo) to break the zoonotic S. japonicum cycle.',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Affects >240 million people globally. S. japonicum is a true zoonosis where treating humans alone fails because livestock continually reseed the water with eggs.',
    onehealth: 'S. japonicum control in China/Philippines relies heavily on treating bovines with Praziquantel or substituting water buffalo with tractors to break the transmission cycle.',
    economicImportance: 'Massive burden on human productivity (DALYs). Reduced livestock draft power and milk production.',
    indianContext: 'Human schistosomiasis is historically absent, though a localized focus was recently confirmed. Animal schistosomiasis (S. spindale, S. indicum) causes hepatic disease in ruminants but is not zoonotic.',
    globalContext: 'S. japonicum in Asia (zoonotic). S. mansoni/S. haematobium in Africa/South America (mostly anthroponotic).',
    recentAdvances: 'Integration of veterinary interventions (bovine vaccination/treatment) into human health programs for S. japonicum.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Waterborne fluke. Cercariae penetrate skin. Pathology caused by eggs trapped in liver. S. japonicum utilizes bovines as major reservoirs.',
    quickRevision: "Fluke, skin penetration, cercariae, freshwater snails, liver granulomas, Praziquantel, water buffalo, Swimmer's itch.",
    references: [ 'WHO Schistosomiasis', 'Merck Vet Manual' ]
  },
  cryptosporidiosis: {
    definition: 'An acute, self-limiting (in immunocompetent) but potentially life-threatening (in immunocompromised) protozoal disease causing severe watery diarrhea in mammals, birds, and humans.',
    historicalBackground: 'Discovered by Tyzzer in 1907. Recognized as a major human pathogen in the 1980s during the HIV epidemic and the massive 1993 Milwaukee waterborne outbreak (400,000 infected).',
    etiology: 'Cryptosporidium parvum (major zoonotic species from cattle), C. hominis (human-to-human).',
    taxonomy: 'Phylum Apicomplexa, Class Sporozoasida, Order Eucoccidiorida, Family Cryptosporidiidae.',
    morphology: 'Tiny spherical oocysts (4-6 µm) containing four naked sporozoites (no sporocysts). Sporulate intracellularly.',
    hostRange: 'Neonatal calves (primary veterinary concern), lambs, foals, humans.',
    reservoir: 'Young calves are the major reservoir, shedding billions of oocysts.',
    vectors: 'Mechanical transmission via flies.',
    carrierState: 'Asymptomatic shedding can occur in adult cattle.',
    envSurvival: 'Oocysts are incredibly resistant to environmental degradation and, crucially, to standard levels of chlorine used in municipal water treatment.',
    transmission: 'Fecal-oral route (ingestion of oocysts from contaminated water, food, or direct contact with infected calves).',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Oral ingestion.',
      spread: "Excystation in the small intestine. Parasite occupies a unique 'intracellular but extracytoplasmic' niche on the apical surface of enterocytes.",
      organs: [ 'Small intestine', 'Biliary tract (in immunosuppressed)' ],
      lesions: 'Villus atrophy, crypt hyperplasia, and loss of mature absorptive enterocytes leading to malabsorptive and secretory diarrhea.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Cell-mediated immunity (CD4+ T cells) is essential for clearance. IgA provides mucosal protection. Immunodeficiency leads to chronic, unremitting infection.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Neonatal calves (1-4 weeks old): Profuse, watery, yellow diarrhea, dehydration, lethargy, tenesmus, weight loss.',
        chronic: 'Rare, usually resolves or causes death from dehydration.',
        subclinical: 'Adult cattle shed oocysts asymptomatically.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Explosive watery diarrhea, abdominal cramps, nausea, low-grade fever lasting 1-2 weeks.',
        chronic: 'Cholera-like, intractable diarrhea leading to severe wasting and death in HIV/AIDS patients.',
        subclinical: 'Frequent in endemic areas.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Hyperemic intestinal mucosa with fluid-filled bowels. Emaciation.',
    histopathology: 'Tiny basophilic bodies (trophozoites/schizonts) attached to the brush border of enterocytes. Villous blunting.',
    sampleCollection: 'Feces.',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'Acid-fast stain (Ziehl-Neelsen) of fecal smears shows bright red oocysts (4-6 µm) against a blue background.',
    rapidTests: 'Direct fluorescent antibody (DFA) test is the gold standard. Antigen ELISA.',
    serology: 'Used for epidemiological studies, not clinical diagnosis.',
    pcr: 'Multiplex PCR allows species identification (vital to distinguish zoonotic C. parvum from anthroponotic C. hominis).',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Calves: Rotavirus, Coronavirus, E. coli (ETEC), Salmonella, Coccidiosis (Eimeria).',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Supportive care (oral or IV fluid therapy) is paramount. Halofuginone lactate can reduce shedding in calves. Nitazoxanide used in immunocompetent humans.',
    drugResistance: 'No highly effective drugs exist for immunocompromised patients.',
    vaccination: 'None available.',
    biosecurity: 'Strict hygiene for calf handlers. Isolation of scouring calves.',
    control: 'Cleaning calf pens, ensuring adequate colostrum intake.',
    prevention: "Boiling water or using reverse osmosis filters (chlorine doesn't work). Pasteurization of milk.",
    publicHealthImportance: 'Major cause of waterborne outbreaks globally due to chlorine resistance. Leading cause of pediatric diarrhea mortality in developing nations.',
    onehealth: 'Protecting human municipal watersheds from agricultural runoff (calf feces) is a critical One Health infrastructure priority.',
    economicImportance: 'Significant losses in the dairy and beef industries due to calf mortality and reduced growth.',
    indianContext: 'Highly prevalent in dairy calves. Major cause of pediatric diarrhea, though often undiagnosed due to lack of specific acid-fast testing.',
    globalContext: 'Worldwide distribution. A ubiquitous waterborne threat.',
    recentAdvances: 'Development of advanced watershed monitoring utilizing molecular detection to prevent large-scale outbreaks.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Causes severe calf diarrhea. Oocysts are chlorine-resistant and tiny. Intracellular but extracytoplasmic. Stains acid-fast.',
    quickRevision: 'C. parvum, calves, watery diarrhea, chlorine-resistant, acid-fast red, extracytoplasmic, halofuginone.',
    references: [ 'Merck Vet Manual', 'CDC Cryptosporidiosis' ]
  },
  giardiasis: {
    definition: 'A common intestinal protozoal infection caused by Giardia duodenalis, leading to acute or chronic malabsorptive diarrhea in mammals and humans.',
    historicalBackground: 'First observed by Antonie van Leeuwenhoek in 1681 in his own stool. Recognized as a true pathogen in the mid-20th century.',
    etiology: 'Giardia duodenalis (syn. G. intestinalis, G. lamblia). Exists as motile trophozoites and infective cysts.',
    taxonomy: 'Phylum Metamonada, Class Trepomonadea, Order Diplomonadida, Family Hexamitidae.',
    morphology: "Trophozoite: Pear-shaped, binucleate ('monkey face'), with 8 flagella and a ventral sucking disk. Cyst: Oval (10-14 µm) containing 4 nuclei.",
    hostRange: 'Dogs, cats, cattle, sheep, beavers, humans.',
    reservoir: "Wildlife (e.g., beavers causing 'Beaver Fever' in hikers) and domestic pets.",
    vectors: 'None.',
    carrierState: 'Asymptomatic cyst shedding is extremely common in adult dogs and cats.',
    envSurvival: 'Cysts survive for months in cold water and damp environments. Moderately resistant to chlorine.',
    transmission: 'Fecal-oral route (ingestion of cysts from contaminated water, food, or direct contact).',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Oral ingestion of cysts.',
      spread: 'Excystation in the duodenum. Trophozoites attach to the mucosal surface via the ventral sucking disk. No tissue invasion.',
      organs: [ 'Small intestine (Duodenum and Jejunum)' ],
      lesions: 'Physical blockage of absorption, microvillus damage, enzyme deficiencies (lactase), and induction of apoptosis, leading to malabsorption.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Secretory IgA prevents trophozoite attachment. Infection is often self-limiting in healthy adults.',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Puppies/Kittens: Acute, foul-smelling, pale, mucoid diarrhea, flatulence, steatorrhea (fatty stool).',
        chronic: 'Intermittent diarrhea, poor coat, failure to thrive.',
        subclinical: 'Very common in adult animals.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'Explosive, greasy, foul-smelling diarrhea, severe abdominal cramps, bloating, nausea.',
        chronic: 'Profound weight loss, malabsorption syndrome, acquired lactose intolerance.',
        subclinical: 'Frequent.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'None specific. Intestines may contain mucoid fluid.',
    histopathology: 'Trophozoites visible on the mucosal surface. Mild villous atrophy.',
    sampleCollection: 'Fresh feces (for trophozoites), fixed feces (for cysts).',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: "Fecal flotation (Zinc Sulfate is best) to detect cysts. Direct smear of fresh, warm feces to see motile 'falling leaf' trophozoites.",
    rapidTests: 'SNAP Giardia test (detects cyst wall antigen in feces) - highly sensitive and commonly used in vet clinics.',
    serology: 'Not useful.',
    pcr: 'Useful for determining assemblages (genotypes).',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Dietary indiscretion, Exocrine Pancreatic Insufficiency (EPI), Tritrichomonas foetus (cats), Coccidiosis, IBD.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Fenbendazole or Metronidazole (or combination) for 5-7 days.',
    drugResistance: 'Increasing reports of metronidazole resistance.',
    vaccination: "A canine vaccine exists but is generally not recommended as it doesn't prevent infection.",
    biosecurity: 'Bathe the animal on the last day of treatment to remove cysts from the fur.',
    control: 'Disinfect surfaces with quaternary ammonium compounds or prolonged boiling.',
    prevention: 'Avoid drinking untreated surface water. Pick up pet feces promptly.',
    publicHealthImportance: "Major cause of waterborne and traveler's diarrhea. Zoonotic risk depends on the assemblage.",
    onehealth: 'Giardia is divided into Assemblages. A and B infect humans and pets (zoonotic). C and D are dog-specific. F is cat-specific. Therefore, not all pet Giardia threatens humans.',
    economicImportance: 'Significant veterinary costs for companion animals. Decreased feed efficiency in livestock.',
    indianContext: 'Highly endemic in both human and animal populations due to contaminated water sources.',
    globalContext: 'The most commonly identified intestinal parasite in the US and globally.',
    recentAdvances: 'Assemblage typing via PCR has clarified that while pets can transmit Giardia to humans, most human infections are human-to-human.',
    keyTakeHome: 'Foul-smelling, fatty diarrhea caused by an attaching (non-invading) flagellate. Diagnosed via SNAP test or Zinc Sulfate flotation. Treated with Fenbendazole.',
    quickRevision: 'Pear-shaped, monkey face, falling leaf motility, fatty diarrhea, fenbendazole, assemblages A/B, zinc sulfate.',
    references: [ 'CAPC Guidelines', 'CDC Giardia' ]
  },
  visceral_larva: {
    definition: 'Visceral Larva Migrans (VLM) and Ocular Larva Migrans (OLM) are human syndromes caused by the erratic migration of nematode larvae, primarily Toxocara canis and Toxocara cati, through human tissues.',
    historicalBackground: 'First described by Beaver in 1952 in children with hepatomegaly and marked eosinophilia.',
    etiology: 'Toxocara canis (canine roundworm) and Toxocara cati (feline roundworm).',
    taxonomy: 'Phylum Nematoda, Class Secernentea, Order Ascaridida, Family Toxocaridae.',
    morphology: 'Adults in dogs/cats are large (up to 10-18 cm) white worms. Eggs are thick-shelled and pitted. Larvae (in humans) are microscopic.',
    hostRange: 'Definitive: Dogs (T. canis), Cats (T. cati). Paratenic: Rodents, Humans.',
    reservoir: 'Dogs, particularly puppies, which shed massive numbers of eggs.',
    vectors: 'Earthworms and flies can act as mechanical transport hosts.',
    carrierState: 'Adult dogs often have somatic (encysted) larvae in their tissues that reactive during pregnancy.',
    envSurvival: 'Eggs are extremely resistant to environmental conditions, surviving for years in soil and parks.',
    transmission: 'Humans ingest embryonated eggs from contaminated soil (pica/geophagia in children) or unwashed vegetables. Dogs infected via transplacental, transmammary, or fecal-oral routes.',
    pathogenesis: {
      entry: 'Oral ingestion of eggs.',
      spread: 'In humans, eggs hatch in the gut, larvae penetrate the mucosa, and enter the portal circulation. They wander aimlessly through the liver, lungs, brain, and eyes because humans are an unnatural host.',
      organs: [ 'Liver', 'Lungs', 'Eye (retina)', 'Brain' ],
      lesions: 'Eosinophilic granulomas forming along the migration tracks of the larvae.'
    },
    immuneResponse: 'Intense Th2 response, characterized by massive peripheral eosinophilia and hypergammaglobulinemia (IgE).',
    clinicalSigns: {
      animals: {
        acute: 'Puppies: Pot-bellied appearance, unthriftiness, vomiting/diarrhea (often passing whole worms), respiratory distress (larval migration).',
        chronic: 'Adult dogs: Usually asymptomatic.',
        subclinical: 'Somatic cysts remain dormant.'
      },
      humans: {
        acute: 'VLM (children 1-5 yrs): Fever, hepatomegaly, coughing, wheezing, profound eosinophilia. OLM (older children): Unilateral vision loss, leukocoria.',
        chronic: 'Covert toxocariasis: Chronic abdominal pain, asthma exacerbation, cognitive/behavioral deficits.',
        subclinical: 'Many infections remain asymptomatic but seropositive.'
      }
    },
    grossLesions: 'Dogs: Adults in small intestine. Humans: White tracts/nodules in the liver.',
    histopathology: 'Eosinophilic granulomas, often with a central necrotic core containing larval fragments.',
    sampleCollection: 'Serum (humans). Feces (dogs/cats).',
    laboratoryDiagnosis: 'Dogs: Fecal flotation detecting thick-shelled, pitted eggs. Humans: ELISA detecting Toxocara excretory-secretory (TES) antigens.',
    rapidTests: 'None routine.',
    serology: 'TES-ELISA is the gold standard for human VLM/OLM.',
    pcr: 'Not typically used for clinical diagnosis.',
    differentialDiagnosis: 'Dogs: Hookworms, Whipworms. Humans: Retinoblastoma (crucial to differentiate from OLM to avoid unnecessary eye enucleation), Asthma, Ascaris lumbricoides.',
    treatmentPrinciples: 'Dogs: Routine deworming (Pyrantel, Fenbendazole). Humans: Albendazole + Corticosteroids (to control inflammatory response to dying larvae).',
    drugResistance: 'Rare.',
    vaccination: 'None available.',
    biosecurity: 'Strict hygiene. Covering sandboxes when not in use to prevent cats from defecating in them.',
    control: "Aggressive, scheduled deworming of puppies starting at 2 weeks of age. Enforcing leash laws and 'poop scoop' policies.",
    prevention: 'Handwashing, preventing children from eating dirt (pica).',
    publicHealthImportance: 'Major neglected parasitic infection in developed countries. A significant cause of preventable childhood blindness.',
    onehealth: 'Highlights the direct impact of pet husbandry and urban park management on pediatric health.',
    economicImportance: 'Veterinary costs for puppy care; human healthcare costs for asthma and vision loss.',
    indianContext: 'High prevalence in stray dog populations results in heavy soil contamination in urban and rural areas.',
    globalContext: 'Worldwide distribution. T. canis is one of the most ubiquitous parasites of dogs globally.',
    recentAdvances: "Growing recognition of 'covert toxocariasis' linking seropositivity to childhood asthma and cognitive delays.",
    keyTakeHome: 'Puppy roundworms cause migrating tissue cysts in children. Prevent by deworming puppies at 2 weeks and picking up feces.',
    quickRevision: 'T. canis, puppies, visceral larva migrans, ocular larva migrans, eosinophilia, pica, sandboxes, deworming.',
    references: [ 'CAPC Guidelines', 'CDC Toxocariasis' ]
  },
  trichinellosis: {
